Claim: There is no free will.
Human actions and choices can be traced back to external deterministic causes.
Empirical evidence is consistent with a deterministic universe that lacks free will.
Science itself is is driven by determinism. The scientific method is presuming causality to find the root causes of certain events.

If determinism is true, then the our understanding that determinism is true is based on chance conditions of physics and chemistry, not reason and logic. If determinism is false, the conclusion is obviously incorrect.

Without free will, the scientist cannot choose what conclusions to draw from these observations, but must conclude what she is determined to conclude. Therefore such conclusions cannot be trusted.

If determinism is true, then the conclusions are based on chance conditions of physics and chemistry, not reason and logic. If determinism is false, the conclusion is obviously incorrect.

Predetermination does not invalidate the proven effectiveness of logic. If determinism is true, not only are conclusions in accordance to deterministic patterns (which makes them logical), but they must be in accordance to such patterns and such patterns must be valid (rendering such conclusions correct).
If determinism is true, all that happens is in accordance to patterns. Patterns which we happen to intellectually grasp and systematize into something we call "logic".
Predetermination does not invalidate the proven effectiveness of logic. In fact causal determinism demands it.

There can still be causality with nondeterminism. Determinism/nondeterminism is not relevant for finding the root cause of certain events. Therefore science is not necessarily "driven by determinism".
Even in nondeterministic events, scientists are capable of understanding the cause of the event's outcome. This is demonstrated by nondeterministic functions.

Consider the simple nondeterministic function: f(x) = x+b, where b is randomly sampled between 0 and 1 every time the function is called. When the result is 100, x must have been between 99 and 100. Scientists can know this despite the event being nondeterministic.
Causality and determinism are two completely different things which do not depend on each other.
Free will is not compatible with our understanding of the mechanisms that govern the universe and, therefore, likely does not exist.
To believe in free will is to believe that cause and effect is not absolute.  In other words, to believe in free will is to believe in magic.

Cause and effect isn't necessarily absolute at every level of the Universe (e.g. at the subatomic level cause-effect breaks down) but things are still inherently causal or random, not determined by human free will.
The laws of physics, as we know them, are either deterministic or fundamentally random. In both cases, they are out of our control.

In computer science, there is an unsolved problem "P=NP?" that represents question of whether computer program execution that is nondeterministic can compute more than corresponding deterministic execution.
P=NP
Scientific interpretations of quantum mechanics are either deterministic or probabilistic (or agnostic on the matter) and no third mechanism has yet been suggested.
Scientific theories (including the laws of physics) are not facts and don't prove anything.  If there is good evidence for free will, then we will have to revise our theories.

This echoes the "Just a theory" argument used by some to dispute evolution by natural selection. Scientific theory is the best and most rigorously tested information available about a subject, not someone's wild idea.
This suggests irrelevance of scientifically proven theories, while, in fact, science has much to say in this dispute.

Scientific theory claiming either determinism or quantum randomness can change in the face of good evidence for free will but currently lacking this good evidence it is justified for humanity to follow the current scientific consensus.Interpretations of quantum mechanics are either deterministic or probalistic (or agnostic), no third mechanism has yet been suggested
The laws of physics are also probabilistic, meaning that events and motivations merely change the distribution of possible outcomes and choices, but don't necessarily determine them.
The claim that physics are probabilistic doesn't contradict the fact that the laws of physics are either deterministic or governed by probabilistic true randomness at a quantum level.
The laws of naturel leave a lot of room to act. Apart from breaking them people can do anything with sufficient knowledge.

If the laws of nature are deterministic they leave only one way to act and thus no room to act. If the laws of nature are probabilistic than we have no control over the quantum randomness and thus we can't make use of this room to act as we have no influence on what one path in this room we shall take.

The research (tests which showed brain activity, before people could report the conscious thought) on which some of the deterministic arguments are based on, is proven to be flawed. Scientific America
The claim that free will is incompatible with our understanding of the machanations of the universe doesn't depend on the results of the cited experiments
There is no scientific (or otherwise) model of the mechanisms that govern the universe that is not compatible with the agency of free actors.
Agency is not free will. "Free actors" is not defined, and asserting that we are "free actors" appears to beg the question.
The Earth orbiting around the Sun was not compatible with our understanding of the mechanisms that govern the universe less than 500 years ago, yet is now accepted as fact.
Just because it's not compatible with our understanding of the universe doesn't mean it's impossible. But it does mean that we have absolutely no reason to think that it is in fact possible.
Saying that our understanding could one day shift to allow for the existence of free will is a poor argument. One could say the same thing about anything from telepathy to tarot reading.
Determinism is not compatible with our understanding of the mechanisms that govern the universe either (i.e. quantum physics).

Determinism is not required to negate any rational conception of free will. It's not relevant that the universe isn't deterministic. Random, non-deterministic events do not lend any support to the existence of free will.
"Free" and "random" are, on their lowest level, indistinguishable concepts and the contrary of determinism.
Free will presupposes that the 'self' is a metaphysical being acting on the physical brain. There is no evidence for this.
Even if there is a "self," defined purely as the "thing making the choices," one logically cannot choose what that self is, and so ultimately any subsequent choices are not "free"
Even from a materialist perspective, the human brain is the thing in question which may or may not exhibit free will.
Since current scientific knowledge is insufficient to support either argument, all arguments of value are logical, metaphysical, moral or religious.
Free will could be the result of intrinsic indeterminism, like in quantum theory, not just unpredictability.

Mathematical and physical models will always improve our understanding of how we perceive parts of reality, but models are not reality. Thus, we cannot conclude anything substantial about if the universe is (D) or (FW) from models.
Quantum theory is not distinguishable from stochastic randomness. Stochastic randomness cannot be subject to will and thus cannot be a mechanism or analog for free will.
There is no scientific experiment that can determine whether or not we have free will, making the claim that "free will does not exist" empirically unsupported.

If I ran an experiment where a monkey can choose a banana or a mango, the monkey reaching out for one doesn't prove that s/he could have chosen the other. Proving that any agent could have chosen something they didn't would require going back in time, which science has shown to be impossible.
It is still not understood how human consciousness work exactly, even if sub-consciousness influence has been proven.
The inexistence of free will cannot be scientifically proven as it would be impossible to put two distinct human beings in exactly the same conditions twice and observe their decisions.
Hardly any claim regarding free will (for or against it) is provable, for this very reason.
To design a study that would investigate the physical state of a person taking important decisions for his life or the life of another person would be close to impossible or unethical.
Outside of real-life, in a computer game or in a lab, a person's decisions are not necessarily freely willed but most likely made out of mood, physical feelings and simply not deeply thought of.
The devices needed to investigate brain activity prior to a decision is not discreet and are not portable, making it hard to wear or use during real-life activities.

A person knowing that his brain activity is monitored for some research experience would probably be influenced in his decisions and may regret taking them, making the research unethical and judiciary risky for impactful decisions.
Sciences (physics, chemistry, etc.) are all based on determination. So if determination itself cannot be proven, nothing at all can be scientifically proven.
Whereas human determination cannot be definitely proven, science explores many material situations in which conditions are controlled enough to establish reproducibility and therefore determination.
Science is not immutable. Scientific laws are not actual laws of nature but a human model of natural laws and are always subject to observation.

The rigorous test of the existence of "free will" require to consider the possibility of a supernatural, metaphysical or non-natural cause for human decisions. Thus, to avoid supernatural arguments for the existence of free will quenches any debate on free will.
If there is a natural cause to your will, it is not "free".
Concepts such as 'supernatural' or 'not-natural' are meaningless. Either something exists or it does not exist. For example, fairies are not supernatural, they just don't exist.

The verification principle deals only in the domain of materialism, and the original claim is regarding a proposed feature of consciousness. As consciousness itself is a meaningless concept by the yardstick of the verification principle, it is not an effective tool for discovery on the topic.
If conscience is deterministic, there should be evidence of processes that lead to decisions in that process, such as the chemical processes that go on in the brain.

There are discrepancies in the "exists/doesn't exist" dichotomy proposed. Our physics paradigm is incomplete, and there are concepts that are mathematically necessary to our understanding of the universe that nonetheless cannot be verified by observation. Dark matter is one such concept.
There is a difference between evidence pointing to something that we currently don't understand (such as dark matter) and stuff that there is no evidence for (faeries).
Dark matter is verified by observation (observation of galaxy clusters and of general gravitational patterns), just not by direct observation (of dark matter - whatever dark matter truly is).

Dark matter has been discovered by updated models of space distribution. This observation presents the opportunity for dark matter to exist. With near certainty we can prove this, sadly we have not created the proper technology required to directly observe this.
'Not natural' is a broad concept, including non-obvious, artificial and non-described. Things that exist or not can be rightfully described as 'not natural'.
If there is no empirically verifiable way of proving there is free will, then, according to the verification principle, free will as a concept is "meaningless" and cannot be meaningfully discussed.
Concepts of a high level of abstraction ("theories") cannot be tested in a single experiment, however must be empirically supported by a set of experiments.
There is no single experiment that can prove by itself the paradigm of "evolution", neither of "creation" or other sets of theories explaining the origin of species.
There is no single experiment to prove the theory of relativity by itself.
Falsifiability is the defining characteristic that distinguishes science from pseudo-science. Falsifiability in wikipedia
The verification principle is self-refuting, for the verification principle itself is neither a tautology nor empirically verifiable.
Scientific experiments are not the only way to empirically verify a concept.
If there is another way, and it is independently recreateable then it will become part of science.
Science has shown determinism in all physical phenomena that make up human body and mind. This is reason enough to take a scientific view.
The human brain is an organ which processes externally acquired information through bioelectrical and chemical signals. It's processes are extremely complex but deterministic.

Science has not proven that the mind is completely deterministic because while the brain is physical, the mind processes, considers, and weighs ideas, which are not physical and thus not bound to physically deterministic laws.
Science is one avenue to discovering truth about the human condition, but certainly not the only one.
Science cannot measure philosophical concepts like free will.
The existence of free will is not a question of values. It is a factual claim about the origins of people's choices. As such, it can be analyzed through empirical science.
The parent is not saying that the argument is one of values, they are saying that the only valuable arguments are those of logic, metaphysics, etc.
Current scientific knowledge is one-sided in its support for determinism (atoms, brain signals, evolutionary psychology, etc.).

Respected fields such as analyzing buisiness incentives for example use a method that essentially ignores religous, demographic, ethical context, etc, taking into account only the incentives (and artifical consequenses estabished by the buisiness), and can accurately predict what the pattern of employee behavior will look like.
Some scientific concepts and observations cannot be explained without the existence of free will.
The multiverse theory implies that one's own eventual "fate" is governed entirely by the choices made by the individual. Destiny depends on free will.
The natural selection of some mental features through evolution suggests the existence of free will.

The existence of doubt, reflection, and self criticism support the existence of agency. The existence of worry and anxiety support the existence of agency. There would be no evolutionary basis for these emotions if we were not able to select behavior from a variety of options.

Anxiety is triggered by certain kind of stimuli or thought like a spider or the thought of death. It's rather a mechanical psychic process, it'd rather be an argument against free will. Anxiety is triggered as a aversive stimuli when a nefarious stimuli is encountered to avoid it. It's rather in favor of a "program line" coded into the brain.
Pain would have no reason to exist if there were not free will. Pain teaches animals about certain kinds of dangers.

Pain is an intrinsic neurological response that serves to protect us from elements that cause physical and/or mental harm and as such serves as an instinctual survival trait. An animal's reaction to avoid pain is not proof that it has free will but is a conditioned response born from its experiential history.
Pain and aversive reinforcement are two component mechanisms of the system that makes our actions deterministic.
Evolution can be entirely deterministic and still work.  The weaker of the species always die out and the stronger thrive.  Computer simulation with fixed seeds show this.
Science can only help to understand the deterministic component of the brain. Tests and empirical evidence fails to test metaphysical theories.

Topics of metaphysical investigation include existence, objects and their properties, space and time, cause and effect, and possibility. Science is just human kind of incremental acquisition of understanding through observation of those things.
There is no evidence that humanity is a special exemption from an otherwise universally deterministic universe.
There is currently very limited evidence that the actions of other species are deterministic.
Consciousness may be a unique human characteristic.  Consciousness is evidenced by all humans experiencing consciousness.
Free will's non-existence is not incompatible with consciousness.

In a theistic universe, free will is plausibly the result of the interaction between an immaterial soul and the human brain. As half of this equation is immaterial, it is not subject to scientific investigation. Therefore, the lack of such evidence in a theistic universe is unsurprising.
The relationship between the universe / world and the soul is unidirectional. While the soul can causally influence the body, the body and world cannot act upon the soul.
Souls are immaterial and immutable.
Similar to a puppeteer is causal in the puppets action but the puppet cannot move the puppeteer.  In the case of the soul there is no physically scientifically observable string.
Anything that can be interacted with can be studied in science. At best, the lack of science scientific results in this area suggested there is no such thing as a soul.
No plausible interaction between an immaterial soul and a human brain has been described that would result in free will.
The universe is not deterministic at the atomic level.
This claim is supported by the Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle.
As the macro-scale universe is a aggregation of micro-scale interactions, it follows that the macro-scale universe is similarly not deterministic.
There is no mix of determinism and indeterminism that allows for a coherent notion of free will
Choices made at random are no more free than those that are determined by prior events. No mixture of randomness and determination is equivalent to having free will.

It is a common misunderstanding about Quantum Mechanics that we can't have a deterministic theory. There are deterministic interpretations of QM. At the moment we only know we can't have a deterministic theory with locality.
A supposed lack of evidence does not indicate that no evidence exists.
No, but it leaves the argument unsupported.

To have a truly ‘free will’, means to be free from external influence. If there exists any factor which originated outside of the individuals own mind, then it is a will bound by external factors/limitations.

Choices are based on the intrinsic nature of a person and their experiences. Neither of these are a person's choice. Therefore, a person's mechanism of choosing is the result of external factors entirely.
If a person's actions cause them to change as a person, that change is still resultant of outside influences, since any action of a person results from external factors.
The two factors "intrinsic nature, and Personal experience" are internal not external factors. The conclusion that the mechanisms are thus the result of external factors, does not follow logically.
This argument suffers from the logical fallacy: Circular Reasoning. It assumes there is no third factor, namely free will, to prove that there is no free will.
This argument neglects that the intrinsic nature of a person may be to have choice in spite of their experiences.
This is a strange claim insofar as it proports that choices do not have an effect on the nature and/or experiences of a person.
Niether Nature nor experience is intrinsically static.

A person's nature and environment determines their choices. Even if the result of these choices further influences their nature, and consequently future choices, it still isn't because of some innate freedom of will. It's just a propagation of choices effecting future choices. If this were a proof by induction, it would be lacking a base case.
The natures of all people are static. An evil person cannot decide to be good, niether can a good person decide to be evil. And if you are somewhere inbetween, there you will stay forever.
The claim in no way states that choices do not have an effect on a person.
No action can be the cause of itself, which is the foundational requirement for free will. Therefore free will cannot exist.
Retrocausality is potentially possible in quantum physics.
However, retrocausality still requires the same deterministic sequence of events to occur in series, regardless of which direction in time they are moving.
"No action can be the cause of itself" is an assumption, not a fact.
As far as we know in physics, and quantum physics/string theory, nothing exists in and of itself without an apparent accompanying cause, except all of reality itself.
This means we are influenced by things, not that we don't have free will.

The concept of influence or manipulation in itself, implies somehow changing an outcome, which means if someone has made a choice (even if it was of their apparent own free will) and there has been an outside influence that contributed to them making that choice, then the choice was not entirely theirs. Or you could say that it was 'determined' by an outside factor.
We act out belief and are unable to control what we believe.
When presented with the right evidence, we have no choice but to believe what we believe (e.g. that 2+2=4 or that this screen is powered by electricity).
Additionally, this argument extends much further into the realm of morality and philosophy. We are unable to change the pain or pleasure we feel for certain actions/things.
People often hold on to an incorrect belief, even when presented with sufficient evidence to the contrary.
Attention is not caused by or necessarily related to a previously "attention thought".
Attention can be both reactive and proactive.
Claiming that attention is free is begging the question. The ways in which a person directs their attention could themselves be determined.
A person is pulled into attention, like a magnet, during a traumatic event. In other words, "Traumatic Attention" is viewed whether or not the witness wants to See/Participate, or not.
"Techniques" then must be created to learn how to properly "view" the "traumatic attention" or analyze the viewed data, before proper emotional responses are given.
Once the "appropriate view" is established, an appropriate reaction" can be made.
Attention is a reflexive reaction to stimuli that we do not control (e.g. an explosion will catch your attention regardless of your will).
It is possible to desensitize oneself to reflexive responses.
Desensitizing against one impulsive input would just shift attention to the next impulse. Desensitization to all inputs would undermine one's attention.
It would still be determined that you teach them these techniques.
Nobody taught the first person. He learned through experience and observation (paying attention).

Besides the fact that there was not really a 'first' person, the experience and observation such a person would have gone through would still have been determined by forces outside their control (genes, environment, etc.).
Unless a being is omnipotent, its will is restricted to a certain extent.
The will has always been understood to exist with regards to available actions in any given situation, not omnipotency. Freedom does not have to be infinite to be freedom.
Where there is existence there are consequences, therefore action is restricted. But restrictions on action do not restrict "will", even when the influence they have is strong.
Just because a will is influenced by outside factors doesn't mean there is no element of choice. To some extent I can choose how I react to what I encounter in the world.

Social context, culture or the way one has been raised may influence moral 'truths' and decision making processes. However, this does not disprove at least some base elements of agency, ie; refraining from suicide.
Having agency isn't having free will. A decision to refrain from suicide is caused by outside factors - genes and environment- just like all other decisions we make.
Humans create new knoweledge to solve problems. Because of this their influence is potentially endless and needs to be distinguished from other objects with the concept of free will.
Being unpredictable by definition still does not grant an individual free will. Just because we cannot predict the outcome of a process doesn't mean that the process is not strictly determined.

But also, your choices will always depend on the social context, the way you've been raised, culture, so you cannot control them in an absolute manner. Realising or not, you opinion might have been shaped by some books you read or thoughts you heard
An 'element of choice doesn't establish that a free will exists. Simply making decisions/choices is not the same making decisions/choices freely.

No person lives whose will was not influenced by externalites. But freedom of will is not the right or state of being left alone, rather it is the right to exercise ones faculties without being immediately destroyed.
Free Will does not require a lack of consequence. Otherwise there would only be free will in the realm of a lone conscience without any outside reality or existence.
External influence didn't limit your free will, it just put you in a position to choose something.
Only if external factors alone determine a response is it bound by external factors.
All internal factors are determined by external factors.
Determinism based on physics doesn't support the common understanding of determinism, and doesn't stand in the way of free will.

We think of dice as being random, and empirical observation confirms this.  We encounter probabilistic processes all the time in nature.  For all we know this probabilistic behavior goes "all the way down".

Determinism based on physical causation inherits the philosophical doubt about causality expressed most famously by Hume: we can't in the end tell the difference between "A causes B" and "A happens then B happens".

Physical determinism implies that it's possible in principle to compute the state of the universe at state t+1 with complete knowledge of the universe at state t, but this is remains impossible because of the indeterminate nature of physical states.
The Three-Body Problem in physics is problematic for physical determinism because the gravitation motion among three or more bodies is generally chaotic and thus indeterminate.

The laws of physics can only ever be approximations, because the evidence for them is data collected from experiments, which always have a degree of uncertainty. There is room in this uncertainty for non-deterministic processes, just as there was room for relativistic effects in the evidence for Newton's laws prior to the 20th century.
Determinism applies to inert matter, and cannot be applied to living organisms.
A person (with free will) is an emergent collection of deterministic parts (atoms). An emergent collection does not necessarily have the same properties as its parts.
For example, a table is a collection of atoms that are in motion. However, we would not say that the table is in motion.
The argument that human beings lack free because they are composed of atoms that lack free will is an example of the fallacy of division.
Non-deterministic properties can't emerge from deterministic systems.
Chaotic dynamical systems exhibit apparent randomness and yet are fully deterministic.
The Newtonian physics problem of rolling dice is a good example: small changes in initial conditions which are not observed or controlled lead to very different final results.
Atoms aren't deterministic.
Humans are not determinable because of the growth of knowledge. Humans achieve new understanding which changes the way they act.
The growth of knowledge is infinite.

Every solution creates new problems. Since humans are fallible our knowelege is imperfect. The causative part in our knowelege solves the initial problem, but the misconceptions create new porblems. This leads to an endless refinery process.
Predicting the growth of knoweledge is impossible, because it entails knowing everything. This is not compatible with the laws of nature.
For instance, it would violate the increase of entropy and energy/information conservation.
Entropy is the idea that all ordered energy in our system, deterministic or free-will, is increasing in randomness.
If we follow the laws of thermodynamics to the nth degree, we are forced to accept the randomness of nature. Even predetermined commitment to randomness doesn't make said randomness determined.

If entropy leads to universal randomness and randomness is the lack of all deterministic forces, then at least one part of a wholly deterministic universe is false, meaning there most be something else influencing the universe outside of determinism.
Entropy does not lead to universal randomness. It's a broadening redistribution of localized energy, not a degradation of cause-and-effect.

At peek randomness, cause and effect cease to have value. This is because cause and effect is only useful if the effect can be made sense of from the cause. As peek randomness is reached this logically would imply that causes create more nonsensical effects.
Cause and effect don't exist at the end point, maximum randomness, because everything is static. Cause and effect only apply to systems in which randomness is decreasing or increasing.

A common interpretation is that thermodynamics uses statistics to analyze complicated deterministic systems. Until this interpretation can be ruled out, thermodynamics doesn't support the claim that the universe is random.

We do not create knowledge, we discover/recall it. Plato describes how a slave boy was able to "recall" some geometric properties, without any further assistance Wikipedia: Meno's slave. Thus he concludes that all knowledge has always been there, we merely remember/discover it.
Not knowing how you will act is not the same as having free will. You could be determined to act in a certain way without knowing it.
There is nothing inherently non-deterministic about gaining knowledge and understanding.
Highly complex behaviors, like creating art, are evidence of free will.
Simple conscious actions are evidence of free will.
The more complex a topic is, the more degrees of freedom there are. This means the more complex such behaviors are, the less predictable their outcomes become.
"Unpredictability" in the sense of computational intractability is not the same as indeterminacy.
Complexity does not imply indeterminism.
If there are no random elements in a system, then that system is deterministic, regardless of its complexity
Computers now can generate intelligible, unpredictable and articulate art. This doesn't mean that computers have free will.
The human brain is a very complex organ. Therefore, complex behaviours emerge from it.
If the variables that determine choices are without limit, free will is still possible, as peoples actions will in the end be fundamentally indeterminable.
Since people's actions cannot be anticipated, free will must exist.
Even if you could build a supercomputer that would actually predict human decisions, there would be free will for human beings because this computer would not be a human being.
There is no free will is effectively the same as saying that a person's choice can be calculated. Since this is currently impossible, there is free will.
The fact that an outcome can't be calculated doesn't imply free will. The result of throwing a dice is random event that can't be calculated. This doesn't mean that the dice has free will.
People's actions cannot be anticipated due to lack of sufficient information about all the factors that determine an individual's decision.

Given the absolute knowledge of one's past, personality, up to the neural patterns of one's brain, we would be able to anticipate every decision that individual makes excluding possible random decisions.

Given the epistemological limits of embodiment, such as not being able to achieve a 'God's eye view' of reality, it is unreasonable to assume that knowledge of all determining factors could ever be achieved by a human agent.
Determinism is not sufficient to explain all of life's choices. Natural events, entropy, and other phenomenon are indicators that at least some aspect of life is chosen.

"The import of the free will theorem is that it is not only current quantum theory, but the world itself that is non-deterministic, so that no future theory can return us to a clockwork universe." [Conway, Kochen, 2009]
Mathematical and physical models will always improve our understandings, but models are not the reality of whether or not our universe is deterministic or not.
Observations in quantum mechanics are influenced by the observer despite the length of time a photon has traveled. [IP video clip, 1m24s]
Whether or not one can identify the cause of another's action does not mean that their will was free.
That would mean that the link between determinism and causality is extremely vague. If that is the case, individuals would be free of any meaningful determinism.
It is wrong to assume that the variables determining our choices are in fact without limit.

Cause and effect for inert matter is exemplified by dominoes falling one after another in a linear chain. In contrast, a line of humans would not fall in a linear way when pushed. Some would fall and others would resist or do something else. This is free will.
The mechanisms that underpin time suggest that everything was determined the moment existence began.
True self-determination is impossible because it requires the actual completion of an infinite series of prior choices.

Galen Strawson's Basic Argument, proposes that: To be truly responsible for how one is at time-point (0), they must have brought it about via time-point (-1). But to have been responsible for how one was at time-point (-1), one must have been responsible for how one was at time point (-2). This regress is endless.
The regresses implied in the paradox of the Arrow or the Sorites paradoxes aren't ultimately convincing. Therefore, not all regresses are convincing.

And what is even more important about Zeno's paradoxes is that Space definitely exist, yet, it is when we try to rationalize its nature that we end up with paradoxical models. Likewise, the paradox of infinite regress on self-determinism shall not be taken to imply that free-will does not exist, just like the Arrow paradox does not imply that space does not exist, for we actually do know it does. If anything, it tells that free-will cannot be completely modeled with a finite-state machine.

This simplistic mental exercise fails to take into account the basic biological realities of human existence, in which the regression has obvious hard and soft limits to extension, which thereby nullify the argument.

Even if T-1 situation pushes me toward a choice, “free will existence” is the proposition that my choice at T0 can still be free, independent of T-1. The first assumption of the regress is already a denial of self-determination and free will, making the whole regress a circular argument.

If only part of the inputs motivating my choice have been freely chose in the past (such like my personality, my beliefs, etc) then a true “free will” is meaningful, because it combines the consistency of the will with the freedom of my choices.
Even if we can only make small choices, we would still have free will.

This is a consequence the Relative Simultaneity results of Einstein's theory of Special Relativity.  The present for one observer may be the past or future for an observer in a different reference frame.

Whereas time appear relative, “if the two events could be causally connected (i.e. the time between event A and event B is greater than the distance between them divided by the speed of light), the order is preserved (i.e., "event A precedes event B") in all frames of reference” according to the source . Causality being preserved, Free will is still possible.

Assuming time as a matter of perception, being it one we experience in a linear way, but not necessarily the only way of experiencing it, everything happens at the same "time", so every action happened, happens and will happen.

Everything that happens, happens simultaneously. The consequence is that time always occurs as the present and is not 'linear': the past consists only of memory operations in the present, and the future is only prediction and cannot begin. The future cannot be determined, because even the operation of predicting the future changes the present and therefore the conditions from which the predictions were made.The Future Cannot Begin

Time brings the perception of change, movement. But that perception is not real if time happens simultaneously. Time is not only the present. Time is past, present and future. Those three stages are the same. The difference is how a being experience it. We experience time in a linear way, but as I said earlier, that doesn't mean it's the only way to experience it. Saying that the future cannot be determined means that the existance is being built, and not already built. Existance is. No past,etc
There are no evidence that time is not monodirectional.

This would mean it is theoretically possible to predict every point in time (also the future) when knowing everything about the moment existence began. If someone knows their future they will act differently and this prediction will not be correct anymore. Hence this prediction can not be made, therefore not everything was determined from the beginning of time.
If everything was determined at the beginning of existence, then the beginning of existence itself is still undetermined, leaving room for free will.
This is a cyclical argument, and presupposes that free will exists.  If free the assumption that free will doesn't exist, the beginning of existence would be determined.
Though more complex than dominoes, human decisions are made through physiology, which adheres to the same laws of physics as any other matter.
Psychology is not a domain of physics.
Psychology is applied biology, which is applied chemistry, which is applied physics.

All other fields (including psychology) are higher-order domains that are governed by the principles of physics. An example of the connection is the field of psychophysics being dedicated to analysing the effects on experience or behaviour by systematically varying the properties of perceptual stimuli along physical dimensions. www.sciencedirect.com
Calling psychology a domain of physics confuses levels of analysis. For example, you can't fully understand the emotion of love by measuring physiological responses to perceptual stimuli.
Apparent randomness in the universe is strong evidence for the existence of free will.
The existence of spontaneous action suggests we have free will.
Even domesticated house cats exhibit signs of free choice, as they exhibit unpredictable behavior that does not conform to the will of their caretakers.

Unpredictability is not an indication of free will. Rather it is the state of not having enough background information in order to make an informed estimate. We can predict the weather but only within a certain percentage of confidence; the more information the higher the percentage of confidence in the prediction. A sudden gust of wind or unexpected rainfall is not proof that the weather has freewill.
The assumption that spontaneous actions exist is unjustified, meaning this is not a self-evident argument.
A belief in "spontaneous" actions as a conscious decision, is confusing conscious thought with subconscious thought. One's subconscious "knows" 7 seconds before you decide something.

Libet's seminal study shows that humans make decisions before they are aware of doing so. As such, by the time we feel like we are making a choice, unbeknownst to us, the decision has already been made.
The test was later replicated by others such as Kreiman and Haynes and others, extended Libet's findings by using more sophisticated technology.
Decisions are a balance between voluntary and involuntary, i.e. conscious and subconscious.
It's free will to subconsciously pre-decide things since our slower and conscious awareness is better for contemplating decisions.
Our conscious thoughts guide our subconscious, and vice versa.
We involuntarily shut our eyes against a strong light, and we can choose whether to shut our eyes against a weaker light.

It may be the case that testing simple mechanical decisions is the very worst way to check for free will, which may be reserved for those decisions which are arise in the most authentic, natural, and creative contexts.
The decisions in the research studies appear to be meaningless. That such a level of non-moral non-impactful decisions are deterministic is compatible even with a libertarian free will.
The subjects have even been ask to act when "they felt the urge to do so", which is a direct demand to follow their physical instinct, and not to freely decide.

Many studies simply look at a choice among random options (such as choosing any letter in a set) which may lead the subjects to simply listen to their brain physical state to take a decision, and not using their actual free will.
Libet's study shows that there is 200 millisecond delay between deciding to act and moving your finger, which may be purely a mechanical problem, and not a deterministic one.
Seeing a physical reaction before a conscious realisation may just as well mean that there is a "lag" in cognition, not that the decision itself was made without consciousness.
We are our brains, so if the decision are made by our brains, they are made by us.
Persons without brains are incapable of making decisions.
If decisions are made by deterministic physical systems like brains, then there was no freedom in the making of the decision.

The brain is not widely regarded as completely deterministic. It achieves some degree consistency by using statistical averaging, but some degree of consistency is not equivalent to complete consistency.
Whether "decisions are made by us" is irrelevant to whether "brain states relate deterministically to brain functions" and its parent relevance for the grandparent.
If a brain does something you are unaware of, and then simply pushes it into consciousness (as suggested by the parent claim), there's no freedom there.
Habitual skills, like those required for sports, performing arts, and skilled labour, are largely reflexive. We find these people highly praiseworthy and responsible for their accomplishments.
There is no genuine praise.
Praise and praising events are often motivated by selfish desires to obtain something from the praised person
Praise of non-personal ideas and dead persons are for political agenda, ultimately motivated by selfish matters (as illustrated by the confederates monuments debate in the USA)
Praise by people that have no special needs are common and support the existence of genuine praise
Praise is a behaviour of exclamation by a person feeling impressed, amazed or proud of the achievement of another. There is no necessity for freewill; it is a directed expression of an emotion.
People with traits that are largely explained by genetic factors - such as height, IQ - and that are thus not dependent on personal choices are often still praised for them.
All actions appear to be spontaneous to the observer, but may indeed be deterministically caused.
The quantum world is intrinsically random.

The simple Newtonian view of a causal universe is disputable because of quantum uncertainty. It can actually be impossible to know the outcome of an even because it is impossible to predict subatomic particles. Therefore, things are not predetermined.
Things not being predetermined doesn't grant us free will; the weather might not be predetermined and we don't think it has free will

Unpredictability is not necessarily evidence of an absence of causality. To the contrary, chaotic systems such as market movements and long-run weather patterns are frequently unpredictable by our current means but remain clearly causal.
Free will depends on the existence of causal powers of the mind, not on randomness.
The causal powers of the mind are metaphysical and cannot be proven to either exist or not exist. As such, in Ayerian terms, they are 'literally nonsensical'

Not knowing or understanding a cause does not equal there not being a cause. We do not have the ability to perceive all of the causes in changes to subatomic particles movement or state, that does not mean it doesn't exist.
The universe is intrinsically non-deterministic, showing true randomness in quantum processes.
Quantum processes are only random as far as we can tell; they might be governed be rules we have not yet found.

Both deterministic and nondeterministic interpretations of quantum mechanics exist. No scientific consensus has been reached as both variations of interpretations so far correspond with all observations.
Causality requires us to consider the existence of demonstrated randomness in the natural world as evidence for a non-natural freely willing cause
A proof that natural world is intrinsically random would solve several unsolved problems. Those are unsolved because nobody knows correct answer to them.

If the natural world is intrinsically random, then  BPP != P, because randomness would allow construction of computer that can perform computation in polynomial time that no deterministic computer can perform. In complexity theory, this problem is currently unsolved.
The randomness in quantum processes could be due to the modelling assumption that only processes that can be measured are modelled.
Particles do not have a classical trajectory in quantum mechanics because it cannot be measured.
Many unintuitive characteristics of quantum mechanics are only unintuitive for people who do not consider the measurements as the defining source for content of the theory.
The Heisenberg uncertainty principle limits strongly what measurements are possible.
Beta decay produces a measurably continuous spectrum because energy is randomly distributed to electron and anti-neutrino. Beta decay in wikipedia
True randomness does not exist.

"Probability" and "probability distributions" are distinct from, and confused with, "random" on a regular basis. Only "probability" and "probability distributions" have mathematical and scientific evidence to support them.
Things that appear random and chaotic still have a root cause even if such a cause can not be observed or measured yet.
Things like coin flips only appear random and unpredictable to observers because it is difficult to measure all of the forces that influence them.
Complex and dynamic systems are indeed chaotic, like weather. However, that does not rule out that true randomness exists, like in quantum mechanics.
Humans have a tendency to call that which they do not understand 'random'.
It is possible that randomness exists despite the fact that human beings mistakenly label things as random.
This statement is not yet proven. Albeit highly likely, it can not be formulated in such a strong manner to make a case.
The Everett Many Worlds interpretation of Quantum Mechanics doesn't have a fundamentally random element.

The Many Worlds Interpretation includes all possible world states under one wave function. This means that there are no unaccounted for universe states, not that there is no random element to the one universe we happen to be in.
The quantum world is considered unpredictable because it lacks a clear pattern, but that does not mean it is random.
Radioactive decay is a well-described stochastic process.
It was argued that particles may, in fact, be freely willing to split.
The deterministic nature of Stochastic processes is yet unknown (á la Bohm) - that does not show that there are events without deterministic cause.
Whereas physical stochastic processes described today may become physically "ruled" in the future, this has yet to be shown and therefore could be ultimately ruled or not.
Tracing back actions and choices is only meaningful in hindsight to see how we arrived, but chaos, randomness, uncertainty, and free will still have a role.

True unpredictability or randomness requires that there is no existing cause for obtaining the specific modality observed instead of any other possible modality. This observed violation of causality leaves room for free will as an ultimate cause.
Randomness is defined as the absence of rule or organization, which can be rephrased in "nothing is ruling or organizing", making "nothing" as the rule and organization
Apperant is to seem real, it doesn't entail things to be real only appear to be real. A stick in the water appears to broken, the sun appears to be close. Both are not what they appear to be.
Free will requires understanding the cause of the choice as oneself, therefore randomness (as a lack of understanding) is evidence of a lack of free will.
Even if the universe isn't deterministic, randomness does not mean we have free will.
In philosophy, a clear distinction is made between randomness and free will.
If randomness underpins our actions, then we can't be in control of them because our actions are random rather than free, undermining the kind of control required for free will.

True randomness does not help the case of free will at all. If all your choices are due to microscopic randomness then it is not free. That would make you no more free to make choices than an electron is free to determine its location in an electron cloud.
Just as life has evolved to combat gravity, we must have evolved in some respect to combat or use quantum mechanics for some benefit.
A non-deterministic will would have to be completely random. Therefore, pure randomness would not be any more "free" than a deterministic will.
Will can be non-deterministic without being completely random.
Will can be self deterministic, and thus not be random.
Pseudo-random number generators are deterministic, produce apparent randomness but are not evidence of free will.

"Not having free will" would mean that one would be able to deduce a choice (with 100% certainty) about to be made in the future, given they have perfect knowledge. However, with a non-deterministic universe, this is impossible.
If a person has a mechanism which chooses one of two outcomes based on a random event which occurs locally within the person's mind, then they were free to choose the outcome.
Their choice would still have been bound by the causal path stemming from the random event, even if the event itself did not have a causal path preceding it.
If your will is randomly made in your mind, it simply puts "nothing" as the one who freely decides. That is not human free will, but the free will of nothingness.
The mechanisms of gene activation in the whole body that determines the whole  human biology is believed to be partly random. But nobody is believed to be freely deciding its whole biology.
The book the origin of individuals deeply investigate the free nature of cells.
The free will of nothing is like putting "Nothing" as a all-deciding Deity
Random means unchosen. A random event cannot be the result of a free choice or any choice whatsoever.
To consider randomness as a meaningful concept, in regards to choice, is biased against the concept of identity, and therefore against free will.
The concept of free will is to accept that “I”, my identity, can be the cause of my decision. If the concept of identity is meaningless, free will is also meaningless.
Assuming that my identity can be the cause of my decision means admitting that my decision is constrained by my identity. My identity, in turn, is constrained by my genes and my past experience.

For an observer, my identity can only be described as causeless, “I have no reason to be who I am”. To consider it “random” suppose that it could have been different, “I could have been someone else” which is meaningless.
Even if on quantum level randomness would exist, asserting that free will would stem from this randomness is implausible
Anything that is random is by definition not chosen. When we do something random, we assume this is "out of character" and thus not really an action chosen by any will.

On a size scale, quantum phenomena is too micro to bear any meaningful information to the macro level of human behavior. There haven't been any observations of relational patterns between quantom phenomena, that would suggest effects on the level of human psychology.
Human actions are determined by uncontrollable internal and metaphysical processes.
Modern science's understanding of the brain suggests it is deterministically linked to human action.
Brain scans show that organic aspects of brain function affect decisions and behavior.
Brain functions can be analysed in great detail and decisions consistently appear to relate deterministically to physical brain states.

Decisions are made by our brain. The brain is physical, so it follows the laws of physics. Free will implies the brain's physics are altered by another decision system (not physical) to work against the result of the "software + hardware" brain system.

The lack of understanding of the relationship between the appearance of the physical body during waking consciousness as mechanical and phenomenal experiences themselves precludes any assertion of evidence of physicalism.
Evidence is only that which is evident to some conscious experience. There is evidence which suggest that consciousness itself transcends the brain, or life itself.
Criminology shows that brain activity and deficiency can contribute to criminal activity.
One should not confuse 'consiousness' and 'free will'. The fact we make uncounsious descisions does not make those descisions 'determined'.
Whatever determines our physical brain states remains unknown.
Brain science is still at a relatively crude stage even after great advancements in the last few decades.
Currently, the way that brains process information and make decisions is far beyond our understanding, thus the data required to disprove free will cannot currently be processed.
If in the unkown part of the decision-making process there is a decisive free-willed element, free will exist and we simply do not know it yet.

Whereas correlations can be found in brain physical patterns before the actual decision, since the processes that lead to these patterns are mostly  unknwon it leaves plenty of room for freely willed conscious elements.
Understanding the biological working of the brain is an arbitrary goal post. The question of free will can be tackled deductively without any knowledge of how this particular process unfolds.

Modelling even single neurons in a realistic manner requires modern supercomputers, therefore there is not enough processing power in the world to simulate the billions of neurons in the entire brain.
All scientific fields are in a relatively crude state compared to future advancements, but we can still construct truth around the current scientific consensus.

Consensus does not mean truth but theory. When it gets to "free will", there is an impossibility to disprove or prove it by using only current scientific consensus, since we are not having a consensus on spirit, consciousness and soul definitions.
Our spirit may be freely determining our physical brain states.

We can easily alter our brain states with predictable outcomes by consuming specific chemicals (e.g. drugs and alcohol). In many cases we know exactly what is determining or altering our various brain states.

The rebuttal that can be generalised to 'even if a phenomenon can be reduced to natural explanations, there could be a magical cause underlying it' are impotent rebuttals. This is because they simply assert the possibility of supernatural causes.

If there is a natural explanation of decisions, a 'will' or 'agent' that can transcend natural explanations is unnecessary.
Such natural explanations do exist.
There is no consensus among researchers about the significance of different findings, their meaning, or what conclusions may be drawn and papers have been written that argue the contrary.
While decisions seem to relate deterministically to brain states, this relationship can be changed through conditioning.

If two distinct area of the brain may be differently involved in the decision process even in the same person and for the same decision, it means that the predetermination is not structural/hardwired but of higher order of abstraction, which leaves room for free will.
If the process doing the conditioning is part of a deterministic system, then changes in the brain don't buy a way out.
In order for free will to exist, some physical aspect of the brain would require the ability to move without being moved. This is physically impossible.

Since some psychoactive substances seem to be able to significantly alter a persons behaviour and personality in a matter of seconds, there is no reason to assume that our actions are governed by anything other then various chemicals in our brain.
A substance can influence a person's behavior without fully determining it.
Alcohol influences a person's behavior but does not determine it (otherwise people would all behave the same under the same amount of alcohol).
Biological discoveries have been made that explain many internal sources of influence that deterministically determine human action.
Evolutionary biology undermines belief in the existence of free will.

Since we evolved from very primitive organisms that don't possess free will, it is not possible that we have free will, since there is nothing in the biology or structure of the forms of life from which we evolved that could have mutated into whatever the source of free will is alleged to be.

It is easy to a say that insects, or animals with limited brain capacities, have no free will and are acting on heredity and environment alone.  The fact that we have an evolved brain, with a consciousness observing our actions, makes us think our consciousness is the controlling agent; when we are simply a more aware animal.
Electrotonic dynamics present as a candidate to resolve the hard problem of consciousness; their presence is emergent and certain and, cuspped, provide a mechanism for free will.
It is speculative to say that primitive organisms do not have free will.

We have many things that the primitive organisms we evolved from did not have, and which we ought not to have by the logic of your argument, including consciousness, self awareness, abstract thinking, etc.

Life seems to evolve in a teleological way. Beings are altered from generation to generation to fit to the environment. Then, even if only the will to survive drives and determines all actions it's still a different type of causality.
If consciousness actually had no bearing on our choices, then it would be irrelevant to our survival, and therefore it would not have evolved in the first place

Even if there is no free will, we do not have access to the predictor of what will happen; we have to somehow cope with that. Having to deal with incomplete information about the world might make consciousness favorable for survival.
Perhaps and maybes are too imprecise for this discussion.
Artificial intelligence deal with incomplete informations, but have not reached consciousness neither self awareness. Consciousness is most likely useless for this kind of problems.
Free will lets us override our involuntary reactions that evolved for efficiency.
Flinching is involuntary so it evolved to be energy efficient, while pursuing a fanciful goal of training months or years to resist flinching is free will (so it isn't energy efficient).
Free will lets us be fanciful in deliberating for a while on choosing a snack, since free will can override energy efficiency.

The simple exercise of suppressing an innate desire (e.g. I am hungry, but still refuse the snacks in front of me) supports the idea that there actually is free will. My body and internal processes are telling me, or even pulling me, in the direction of eating the snacks, yet I choose not to eat the snack.
Suggesting that determinism would also favor choices which are not favorable for survival is a direct denial of a Darwinian evolution.

Darwinian evolution is not a process that produces perfect organisms. It is a statistical process that reduces the frequency of genes that tend to limit an organism's ability to reproduce. This does not preclude the capability of any individual to undergo random change.

Darwinian evolution can produce empathic agents. The genes within a group of cooperating animals are at times more likely to proliferate when those animals cooperate as opposed to acting purely in self interest.

Unless food is sufficiently scarce, an animal’s not eating all it can every chance it gets does not necessarily put it at significant risk. Moreover, if food is plentiful enough and little effort is required to get it, an animal’s having certain inhibitions associated with eating could increase its chances of survival and procreation. Overeating can expose an animal to increased risks to its health.
Action and inaction are both decisions and both have an origin. While the mental origin is insulated by layers of abstraction it's still deterministic.
"You" deciding not eat the snack is a yet another internal process called reasoning. Both processes being just groups of interconnected neurons reacting to each other.
In such a scenario, one simply succumbs to the desire for control instead of for food.
A regulatory system on top of basic autonomous behaviour is very simple. It in no way requires the addition of free will.
Such a regulatory system also in no way requires the addition of a feeling of participation and will.
Since it is indisputable that we do experience feelings of will, we are compelled to consider the modus tollens case as well as the modus ponens.
MT: Since feelings of will exist, something more than nested regulatory systems is required to explain them.
MP: Since nested regulatory systems can account for the totality of behavior of human bodies, feelings of will must be a feature.

The point is that such a regulatory system (conceivably) *allows* for a feeling of participation.  Therefore, the model is not ruled out by an experience of participation.  This removes the logical necessity from your MT case.

It depends on how we are treating conceivability. To me, it is no more conceivable that a deterministic universe could conjure up anything like participatory experience than it would be for a perfect circle to also be square. We would need a hypothesis of why and how  such a thing as 'will' come into the picture of mechanical regulation before it can be considered conceivable an any effective way.
A feeling of participation and will is not necessarily inconsistent with Determination.

When viewed prospectively rather than retrospectively, the existence of a feeling of participation has no parsimonious justification in a deterministic universe. A puppet which feels it is not a puppet doesn't really make sense.
A choice is made in focusing one's willpower, but there is always a reason, a cause for focusing willpower. Thus if there is a cause the independence of the action is diminished if not eradicated.
Research on the gut microbiome seems to indicate that the bacteria in your gut drive your food choices.

Different bacteria in the gut have different nutritional requirements. They emit signaling molecules. Because the gut is linked to the immune system, the endocrine system and the nervous system the signals have the capability of directly affecting behavior.  This means that what you call free will may just be some bacteria in your gut or other part of your body that has a requirement.
Our DNA impacts our decision-making subconsciously.

DNA, without changing, codes for the development of the embryo, puberty, and other life events through complex step-by-step coding system. If our DNA is able to code cellular decisions one by one, may be also human decisions.

Some parts of the body may still grow after death; bodily mechanics continue to work automatically. This means some DNA is still active postmortem. If DNA was the source of consciousness, there would be some consciousness remaining postmortem. DNA is the information, it is not the source of information. Exactly the opposite conclusion follows: DNA is determined by consciousness, not the other way around.

If DNA is determined by consciousness, you would be conscious before the making of your DNA, which is the fecondation of the ovocyte of your mother. Such pre-existing consciousness is not commonly observed.
There is no proof of absence of consciousness post-mortem, but only absence of communication.
There is a proof of brain activity being zero a.k.a. "flat line".
DNA is not coding cellular decisions, it only determines the actions of cells.

Since deciding can be defined as the selection of a course of action, the centralized and complex mechanisms of selection of a course of actions during cellular differentiation can be described as a cellular decision process.
Cells do not select.

Introducing this as an argument for the existence of free will implies that free will can be found at the level of DNA, i.e. genetic material is somehow free to choose how it is expressed. There is no evidence that this is the case.

The assumption is that the starting point of a behaviour or making a choice, is a thought. Maybe thoughts are the end result of biological stimulus like "body is low on energy" and you think "hungry". Why would "free will" be any different?

The Hard Problem of Consciousness is to find any justification for thoughts and experiences in the first place. If the body is low on energy, then the body would simply prioritize food-seeking behavior. The existence of hunger experience is a phenomenon which only makes sense if there is an agent with the freedom to act willfully that can choose how to respond to it.

This may be begging the question, since there may be no way for free will to make itself 'evidence' from a third party perspective. Looking at traffic patterns of a city from an aerial view, there is no evidence of drivers or the role that their intention plays in determining the behavior of vehicles.
If 'many internal sources of influence' determine human actions, it does not follow that these influences cause human action necessarily rather than contingently.

Sources of influence that are internal to me are part of me and thus expressions of my free will. You can't say I don't have free will and at the same time agree that the locus of decision is internal to me because that admits the existence of free will.
It is a faulty generalization (en.wikipedia.org) to say that all actions are biologically influenced just because many are.

Neuroplasticity suggests that the "individual" and their choices shape the physical structure of the brain. For example, when you learn to play the guitar you make physical changes to your brain, improving auditory processing and hand coordination.nature.com
Phenomena that are native to a high level of abstraction can be very difficult or practically impossible to see at a lower level.

"... we are only just beginning to understand the foundations of human intelligence and consciousness that cannot be captured in an algorithmic formula divorced from the functions of the body and the long evolution of our species and its microbiome." washingtonpost.com

'Chairs' and 'atoms' exist on different levels of abstraction but it's not useful to say that, on the atomic level, chairs don't exist. To say so would deny the real, atomic level physical correlate which the concept of 'chairs' attempts to describe.
It would be entirely accurate to state that chairs do not exist on the atomic level; it would in fact be the only reasonable expression one could make with respect to the question.

Analyzing trees in great detail would show no obvious signs of forests. Similarly, free will is ultimately a result of physical brain functions but it may be practically impossible for us to see or comprehend it at that level.
High-level phenomena are subject to constraints imposed by the nature of their parts, and how the parts interact.
Science cannot explain or understand consciousness. Therefore, this question is outside the bounds of current science.
Our decisions are often emotionally charged. Therefore, one could say we play with loaded dice.
This certainly seems to be the case and is the most reasonable statement we can honestly make on the subject; however, not knowing where free will starts and ends leaves it in question all together.
Our thoughts and feelings create themselves. We cannot directly affect what we think or feel.

On a practical and experiential level creatures that do not comprehend all of the inputs to their own thinking process act and think (and are better off acting and thinking) as though there were free will -- so free will exists not as a fundamental truth but as an heuristic.
The illusion of free will is the phenomenological experience provided in the event that a future response to present sensory information has not yet been made conscious.
Free will is merely the label used to describe the many complex processes that contribute to decision making, like the hormonal, digestive, and nervous systems in the body.
Humans do not have an immediate access to the complex processes that contribute to decision making.
Our immediate inability to perceive the causes of events with our senses does not impede out ability to understand them in any other arena.
While we cannot perceive the barometric changes and distant atmospheric conditions that cause a storm we nonetheless believe in their existence and reality.
All constructs are an attempt to label phenomena. This fact is independent from and logically neutral to the validity of the concepts themselves.
Whereas many stimuli influence our decisions, none can be described as being the final decision-maker. Only “me”, the subject, is the decision-maker.
The aggregation of "non-free" parts does not generate freedom.

Free will is necessarily used in the production of any claim about free will. When we make a claim about free will, it is based on our ability to freely choose to make that claim, and the ability for others to freely change their position to agree with it.

To say that something is rationalizing implies that there is some agency which has the power to act on its preferences. Something with no free will could not choose whether to believe in free will or not. Belief itself isn't really coherent without an assumption of agency with some degree of potential freedom.

The fear of the "rise of machines" is because we fear that intelligent robots, which are very complex puppets, may reach self-awareness and decide to take over, whereas they would still be non-free pre-determine & programmed machines.

The fear of a computer revolt may be completely irrational, borne out of a deterministic view of consciousness. If we are more than biological machines, then most of this fear is irrational and it would be just a circular argument to use this fear to defend determinism.
Careful attention to the contents of consciousness reveals that thoughts and intentions simply arise in the mind, rather than being deliberately invented by a conscious self.
Given the confirmation of "Wheeler's Delayed Choice," even down to the atomic level, things happen as they happen, with no room to alter the outcome.

It may be the case that consciousness is so fundamental that the modes of inquiry we choose to pay attention to influences the results of that inquiry. If we limit our inquiry to the behavior of 'atoms' observed as a consequence of marrying our perception of tangible and visible phenomena with a tangible and visible instrument's capacity for detecting the same, we may be erroneously dismissing our other capacities for perception of the intangible.
Thoughts and intentions can also me made to arise on demand.

If true, this claim cannot have been invented "deliberately", that is, it is not the product of careful consideration and deliberation of the evidence. It "simply [arose] in the mind". This destroys all warrant for any belief in this claim.
This argument is applicable to each and every statement, causing an infinite regress which renders it meaningless.

The truth of the rebutted claim is contingent on the truth of determinism. The infinite regress is avoided if a free agent can actually deliberate and consider arguments for a position. 

If, on the other hand, we cannot deliberate and consider arguments as free agents, the statement above the product of thoughts that simply arose in the mind, and cannot be considered meaningful.

As long as consciousness is not fully understood (such as the binding problem), it is difficult to determine to what extent we have control over our thoughts. Even if thoughts are largely mysterious, we seem to have some control over them.

It may be the case that our attention cannot exercise itself as both will and awareness of will at the same time. Just because will may be beyond our introspection does not mean that introspection ability is authoritative.
Psychological studies suggest that we have the power to direct our thoughts and feelings.
We can similarly control our reactions to thoughts in general. PTSD recoverers are a good example of this.
CBT is a fantastic framework to see this in action. As a result we can control / modify how we feel about certain things with mindfulness (similar to meditation) and logic.

The decision to direct ones thoughts in a certain direction is itself not free. It could be based on advice from a therapist, or inspiration from a book, or just a previous thought, but there are always outside influences that ultimately determine the decision being made.
The practice of meditation or mindfulness is aimed at providing the practitioner with more control over their thoughts and feelings.

Meditation doesn't create control over one's thoughts. It creates a space in which one can become more directly aware of one's thoughts arising and passing away. Trying to control thoughts is in fact discouraged in mindfulness practice.
Our decisions and perceptions are inevitably shaped by our past experiences.
Studies have shown that past experiences shape people's decision-making process.
As Sartre said, 'Freedom is what you do with what's been done to you'. You can choose, but your options are already set by your past experiences.
Yet, Sartre famously argued that humans not only have free will, but are 'radically free'.
Every decision is determined by one's circumstances, preferences, and what one thinks is true, none of which are within one's control.
What people believe to be true is not the result of their choosing to believe it.
One cannot choose to believe a lie.
If one could choose what they believe, persuasion would not be possible.
If someone understands 2+2 = 4, they cannot choose to believe 2 + 2 is something other than 4.
Whether one understands something is not a choice.
Doubt, for one, is a common vehicle that can access the opportunity to control what you think is true.
Doubt is itself a belief (that another belief may not be true).
Doubt, like belief, involves zero choice. One either doubts a proposition because they find it lacks convincing evidence, or they believe it based on whatever reasoning was presented to them.
Introspection reveals that preference is not a choice.
One cannot choose to like something they dislike.
Pavlovian conditioning demonstrates one can learn to like something they originally disliked through positive association.
The process of conditioning demonstrates the change from dislike to like was not a choice, for if preference was a choice, conditioning would not be necessary.
Introspection reveals that one discovers their preferences rather than setting them.
When tasting food, one discovers, rather than chooses, whether one likes the food.
Our circumstances (country of birth, genetics, family, etc.) are predetermined without choice.
If this were true, psychologists would be able to predict behavior with absolute certainty. However, there is no evidence that they can even come close.
Human fallacy does not negate the limited and predetermined variables of human decision making.
Something being predictable in principle doesn't imply that humans should be able to predict it.
That may be so, but it still demonstrates a lack of evidence for determinism being true and suggests determinism is false.
No prediction can be absolutely certain.
People often make random guesses or choices.
Humans are uniquely capable of making decisions randomly through the use of tools like dice or coins.
If the outcomes of the dice are uncontrollable, then making decisions based on those outcomes means that the basis for these decisions is not within ones control.
Randomness may be a possible preference.
Randomness is, by definition, unpredictable, and thus decisions stemming from randomness are not within our control.
Making a random decision is still based on what options are available.
Decisions inherently come from behavior.

One researcher argues that smoking does not infringe upon free will, despite only having the binary choice of smoking or not. The motivation caused by smoking does not make it impossible to stop smoking. Hence, free will exists.
The ability to quit smoking does not prove or imply that free will exists. Addiction, quitting and relapse could all be pre-determined.

The significant effort it takes to quit smoking is evidence against free will, for if we were able to shape our thoughts, desires and actions freely, the conditioning required for such behavioral changes would not be necessary.

Everything that shapes behavior can be traced back to genetics and upbringing, neither of which involve choice. Therefore, if decisions come from behavior, and we lack authorship of our behaviors, then we lack authorship of our decisions.

It often happens that people will to do that which is not available or in their actual control. Such that one could will to have wings and fly. Thus Ultimate decision is not the ultimate reflection of the will.
Irrational fears, racism, sexism, etc. are not consciously decided things - they are generally placed in the unconscious or subconscious before they come to the fore.
Past experiences play a big role in our decision making process but in a combination of free will, the freedom of giving more or less importance to these experiences and their outcomes.
Humans are bound by their personality, meaning they do not have the ability to truly choose freely.
"Man does at all times only what he wills, and yet he does this necessarily. But this is because he already is what he wills."—?From Ch. V of Schopenhauer's essay On the Freedom of the Will
Personality is a combination of nature and nurture, neither of which we have much control of during our upbringing.
While nature is derived biologically from your parents' DNA, nurture is dependent on your upbringing, culture and environment, none of which can be controlled.

We may not have control over inputs, but we do have control over outputs.
