The combination of nature and nurture and experience that created me in this moment is the array of possible information I could use to defeat any given task. The brain is capable of choosing between different choices based on an internal weighing of pros and cons.

Weighing pros and cons is an example of the exact opposite of free will. If a decision has many more cons than pros, then you realize that it is a bad decision, and you are not free to decide in that moment that it is a good one.
Humans freely build their personality, not from the scratch, but on the foundation conditioned by inheritance, environment etc.

To say humans are "freely" building their personality implies free will in the first place. Just because choices can influence a person's personality doesn't mean that those choices themselves are free.
Free will becomes possible when people become aware of all things that are entering their perception and unconsciously influencing on it.
Being aware of everything influencing your decisions is still itself an influence on your decisions. It'sturtles all the way down.
The Cogito Model of free will argues that random events occur within human brains and bodies, and these random events can be used by a human to choose between two or more actions.
Metaphysical introspection has led us to consider thoughts as a product of subatomic randomness, making human decision the ability to shape these apparently random events.
Since atoms and particles act in probabilistic ways and our brain is made up of atoms and particles, our brain most likely exercises free will.
It has been argued that particles may, in fact, have free will.
To say that a system is probabilistic means that we don't know which will be the concrete outcome of that system at a given time. This is not so say that the system has free will.
DNA mutations in cellular divisions are described as random events.

In the context of free will: there's no strong evidence that quantum-level effects have any impact on information processing done by the brain. What we can measure seems to follow classical rules entirely.
Even if the computation is causal, the interaction of a causal system with a random, or probabilistic, stimuli means that the computation was not deterministic.

If the randomness of the stimuli has no discernible manifestation on the macro-level and the macro-level functionality is instead defined by a probability distribution it follows that, for all intents and purposes, the macro-level system is indistinguishable from a deterministic system.
Quantum mechanics are intrinsically probabilistic, however Quantum Computing relies on the distinction between probability and random noise.
Then what we get is something that many would not consider free will: All our actions are random, we are just living dice.
Actions caused randomly cannot be said to be "willed".  I may deliberately choose according to preference, or I may follow a random course. These two options are mutually exclusive.
It is possible to choose to do something against one's bodily preferences, making it appear random for the natural world.
For example, a young soldier may prefer to live, but may choose to sacrifice his life to protect others.
Lived experience and observation suggest that we have free will.
Overcoming urges and desires is the experience of free will.
Wanting to overcome an urge or desire is an urge or desire within itself.
Humans are bound by instinct, which impinges on our ability to act freely.
Human will is enslaved to the pursuit of pleasure. This is not freedom, but a bondage of the will.
Desires are often described as the results of biological processes, such as hunger, tiredness, affective needs, sexual attraction, addiction, etc.
The pursuit of pleasure cannot be considered as freely willed since it is defined by each person’s individual and cultural perceptions which are, in turn, bound by unconscious desires.

Because our drive for pleasure is most often for that which is immediate and not in a person’s best long-term interests, it leaves us settling for that which leaves us least happy. This cannot be considered free will, but truly bondage.
It is nevertheless possible to supersede the desire for instant gratification, showing it is not a constraint on our will but rather an obstacle that can be overcome through the will.
The brain is forever in pursuit of substances like dopamine that form the main internal reward for things we do. The pursuit of dopamine is often the base for addiction to gambling, drugs, etc.

Free will is an alternative to instincts. Deciding what is favorable or not gives a choice to person with free will, to act accordingly or not. Humans are notorious for choosing less favorable options, like cigarettes.

"Deciding what is favorable" is also not something that a person can directly control. Either you realize that something is favorable or you don't. If it is evident that something is favorable, you can't choose to decide otherwise or vice-versa.

The act of overcoming or suppressing a desire is consistently spurned by a reason to do so, be it conscious or subconscious. Without this reason, which we cannot control, we do not act against these desires, and thus, are simply subject to an alternative influence that overpowers the desire.
The universal human experience of having our will frustrated, diminished, augmented or compromised is a sound basis for considering free will a legitimate phenomenon.

These are indeed perceptions that people have -- the apparent experience of free will is a phenomenon. The question is whether this experience reflects some necessary truth about how the world actually works.  The phenomenon itself does not present support for that conclusion.

To exclude phenomenal appearances from 'the actual world' imposes biases about 'actuality' which ultimately are based on phenomenal appearances. Not to say that appearances can't be deceiving, but even deception and 'actuality' are only phenomenal appearances that relate to the exercise of will. We have to ask why it would make sense that any such thing as a feeling of free will could exist in a world which has no purpose for them nor concrete means to generate them.
The universal human experience of direct, voluntary participation in their own experience is a sound basis for treating free will as a legitimate phenomenon.
It is necessary to believe in free will as humans could not function without it.
If empiricism is true, then someone that acts “as if” they are free, is free.
In our daily lives we frequently act as though we are free, as when we take precautions, like checking when we cross the street.

If that person never learned to look or didn't perceive the danger before they walked, they wouldn't look. Learning (from experience or from others) is a part of their past, perceiving danger is a learned skill, and thus the quote is meaningless.
Our understanding of what 'freedom' is is based on our observation of what we define as 'free' its thus circular logic to argue that if someone looks 'free' they are.
If they are merely "acting" free, then they are not free. Limited freedom is not freedom. Therefore, we do not have free will.
Holding determinist beliefs can foster nihilist viewpoints and lead someone into inaction or destructive behaviour.
If free will is needed to think or live, then free will is real as far as we can tell since any claim of free will inexistence is irrational because impossible to think coherently.
Determinism impairs the decision making process by relieving an individual of personal responsibility.
The question is whether "free will" exists, not if believing in a lack of "free will" is immoral.

The main question is a question of inquiry (whether p); not a question of doxastic deliberation (whether to believe that p or not). Although pragmatic argument can decide questions of doxastic deliberation, they cannot decide questions of inquiry, since they do not bear on the fact of the matter, whether p or not.
A truth that would eliminate your ability to live a proper life could be morally wrong, not true.
If no human being can safely consider a proposition as "true", there is no coherent and valuable point in considering this proposition as truth for the human race.

Since truth is a concept, it is not fully external to human ability to think, and therefore it must not be considered as independent of it. If human ability is unable to grasp something that would be considered as "true" by a different mind/system, it would still be "not true" or untrue for human beings.

If the pursuit of truth has no use (if you die/lose your mind when finding the truth, you obviously can't use it), you would need an inherent virtue to keep believing it's coherent to pursue the truth.
The point of considering "unsafe" propositions that might nevertheless be true would be to pursue truth.
There is no inherent virtue for a human being to pursue the truth independently of the human mind.
A truth that would eliminate your ability to think is not worth thinking - it is not humanly true.
Whether a "truth" is "worth thinking" has no bearing on whether the proposition is true. The thesis is whether a proposition is true, not whether it is better to believe.
What is "morally wrong" can never be involved in support for something being true or false.

No matter how truth is defined in a system, assuming the system is consistent, the system contains some well-defined set of forms which constitute the totality of valid steps of reasoning in the system. In no accepted axiomatic system is "what is morally wrong" referenced conditions for a valid step.
It may be necessary to create a new axiomatic system which includes morality to fully test the existence free will.

Axioms aside, a new axiomatic system could only fundamentally contribute to establishing a proposition if the new system is not expressible in an existing axiomatic system. Which arguably contains most if not all arguments that have been considered. The need for a fundamentally different extension would therefor be remarkable and unlikely.
Nihilism does not inherently lead to destructive behaviour. A person can be a nihilist and still live a happy productive life

This point supports the view that there is no free will by illustrating that we in-fact must act a certain way as to avoid so-called destructive behavior. It is precisely the absence of free will that causes avoidance of behavior deemed destructive.

This begs the question implying that there is a free decision making process that can be impaired. A determinist would argue that all choices are unavoidable and that the beliefs that go hand in hand with them are held inevitably.
An appeal to consequences is a fallacy. The unpleasant implications of a position have no bearing on its truth.

Because free will is the mechanism by which many believe they avoid sin and culpability, they are terrified to imagine that there may be no free will, for fear of damnation; and so they are strongly compelled to believe they are in control of their actions.  This discredits the rationality of believing in free will among those who believe in sin in a way that suggests it is out of fear, rather than logic or evidence.

This response conflates two different types of question: questions of doxastic deliberation (whether to believe that p) and questions of inquiry (whether p)(Zalabardo 2010). P may be false, but I can have good pragmatic reasons to believe that P, regardless of its truth value(Rinard 2017). See literature on Possitive Illusions (DeWeese-Boyd 2017) and Adaptive Misbelief (MacKay & Dennett 2009) for several examples

Evaluations of truth depend on the observer's faculties of perception and reason and how they interact with the world. Thus, the consequences of a so-called truth on the observer's abilities are worth considering when evaluating the veracity of a statement.
Whereas the definition of truth is controversial, none of them are independent on an observer.
For a truth to be falsifiable, it requires an individual conducting a test and observing the results of it.
Truth is not by definition dependent on an observer and rather depends on other assumptions. See for example the Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy.plato.stanford.edu
Truth is not a consequence of an interaction between perception and reality. The intended term seems to be belief or knowledge.
This only proves that living in a lie is easier than facing reality.
Societies and legal systems depend on the notion of free will.

A presumption of free will is the basis for many of the pillars of modern society. Concepts such as justice, praise, and fairness are consequential at the level of human interactions and would not exist without free will.
If there is no free will, then our whole justice system will need to be scrapped; because it relies on you choosing your actions.
If free will did not exist, it would be morally wrong to incarcerate individuals, fine them or sue them for their actions.
Free will is a practical experience and a foundation of society. Without free will, all morality would be relativized and courts will be full of cases against causes, instead against criminals.
Perhaps this demonstrates an inherent flaw with the justice system
The truth of the claim "there is no free will" does not depend on whether there is difficult or technical work to be done.
It may be the case that the Justice System uses free will as a useful fiction to understand people's actions, regardless of whether it is true.

It would be wrong to criticize or correct any actions at all as the very concepts of "wrongdoing" becomes absurd. Since throughout current societies and all past ones, this has to been the case -- humankind unanimously agrees on the existence of free will.

Justice, equity and fairness can exist without the acknowledge of free will. Equity and fairness is about possibilities. And justice is the administration of punishment to the ones who break a consensual code of behaviour, it doesn't reffer to wheter you were conditioned or not.
Something being the basis of many of the pillars of modern society doesn't mean it is true.
The concept of free will is necessary so that humans feel like they have a responsibility to choose right over wrong.
Free will is a crucial concept for the use of 'should' or 'ought to' These concepts lie at the heart of all society's legal systems which keeps citizens in check to avoid chaos from ensuing.
If there was no free will, humans would just capitulate to their appetites and desires without considering how it would affect others for they would feel justified in abandoning their reason.

Thomas Hobbes famously tackles this question. It is reasonable and logical for humans to form societies which restrict these appetites because otherwise life would be "solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short." Complex and restrictive societies arise as a natural economic consequence of humans' survival instincts. In this model, empathy is actually an evolutionarily advantageous animal behavior we've bred into our own population.
If there were no free will, then humans wouldn't be able to choose right over wrong in the first place, nor would there exist any feeling of 'choosing' anything at all.

Illusion of choice would still exist, because conscious processes would still be as they are. Only difference is more objective understanding of what human choices are based of when observing and analysing human environment.
We must necessarily assume other people have free will if we are to successfully communicate and socially interact with them.
Our abilities to have social, rather than just instrumental, interactions with others are predicated on the assumption that we are dealing with non-trivial agents.
Non-trivial agency is not dependent on free-will and can exist in its absence.

The onus is on the claimant to demonstrate how this is possible. Furthermore, this argument is not whether free will "exists", but whether it must be attributed to other people for social interactions to be possible.
Deep emotional conversations happen in works of fiction without the characters needing free will.

Writing a fictional work requires attributing free will to the (generally anonymous) readership, and writing it in such a way that the readers would choose to read the work in the first place, and are satisfied enough with it to continue once they've begun reading.

Well, they're works of fiction.The author hasn't given the characters free-will. The author is a totalitarian whom decides everything they say and do - more evidence of his free-will to write and decide who these characters are.
Our ability to comprehend those social interactions in fiction are dependent on our ability to relate them to the kinds of social interactions we have previously experienced with other people.
Most social interactions between humans are trivial, often ranging from small talk to solving simple problems, and thus do not depend on any assumptions.

'Thank you' and 'please' are evidence of free-will. We, as social creatures, understand the person across from us has no obligation to help - they utilise their free-will to choose. 'Thank you' and 'please' are rewards for choosing to help us.
Even the semantics of small talk contains implicit references to the free will of those involved.
Human beings recognize the capacity for others to choose otherwise, which give simple social conventions meaning.
This is implicit in social conventions even if the other person does not have a choice in the matter (e.g. thanking a shopkeeper).

The practical requirement for the assumption of free will's existence does not confirm it's existence, merely it indicates that human's are not sufficiently computationally robust to accurately analyse the complex system that is another person, and instead must treat them as free agents to avoid energetically and systemically taxing cognitive processing in every social interaction.
Actions can only be moral if agents have the choice to be moral. Morality is a crucial concept for the proper functioning of human societies.
Entities without agency cannot be held accountable.
A tree is not morally good for bearing fruit.
A tornado is not immoral for destroying a family.

An intentional actor is not necessarily a free one. A person who intends to murder another may not be free -- either because determinism is true or because they have an organic brain condition -- and yet a murder underpinned by the intention to murder is still immoral (for its intentional impact on wellbeing).
A person with an organic brain condition murdering is immoral because a person has a responsibility to handle their mental faculties.
Meditation, pain medication and therapy can change people's brains.
Many societies function as if there is not free will.
Most societies today and throughout history rely on deterrence, punishments, and rewards to shape how people behave, which suggests that free will is not a societal need.
Collective belief in something has no causal efficacy to bring something into existence.

There is a difference between a useful simplification of a system and the actual nature of that system. For example, it is often useful to assume that projectiles are travelling in a vacuum in order to predict their trajectory, but that doesn't mean they are actually doing so.
Black holes and other cosmic wonders have existed long before anybody ever believed in them or even imagined such things could even exist.
There are several sound bases for free will which are independent from any presumed social construction. The indirect social experience of other people's will and intention is one of them.

Belief in free will in a deterministic universe is simply a predetermined belief. By the same token, belief in determinism in a deterministic universe is a predetermined belief. Neither side "chooses" what they believe.
Belief in free will is not universal, therefore the existence of this metaphysical concept is not guaranteed.
Buddhists reject the concept of free will consequently people can and do function without it.
Social constructs with no sound basis are simple methods used to impose an unfair society - something people tell you to make you serve their ideology/serve them.

The origin of the irrational concept of free will may be similar to the origin of the "evil persons" concept. Both irrational concepts could have been invented as a justification for moral authority and punishment against persons who were claimed to have been "born evil" or to have "chose evil".

Necessity for the sake of functioning implies the opposite of free will because necessity relations limit freedom and variation. If it is necessary to have free will to exist, then necessity relations that constrain free will must also exist.
Through meditation, people have experiences in which they can directly notice their thoughts and emotions rising and falling without any self willing them to do so.
The existence of the this 'you' can disappear with meditation. Therefore, consciousness is just the awareness of your thoughts and other experiences, which doesn't involve their creation.

Experience and observation don't suggest we have free will. They show we have a will (the craving, desire or intention to act in certain ways), but neither suggest we can do anything in any non-predetermined way.
A human mind can overcome a strong craving.
Humans are capable of overcoming addiction by force of will, even if the addictive desire remains.
The factors that ultimately determine whether or not an individual overcomes a craving are still themselves deterministic.

The will is experienced as a live event which is experienced as the cause of itself (ie. the experience is the cause of itself). Thus prior states are not causative linked, or else they would be part of the same experience.
Observation always changes reality. Just being aware of one's self alone can elevate their adrenaline or other chemical balances in their brain. One cannot separate observation from reality.
Practitioners of meditation do it with intention. Before meditation, they choose a goal or outcome they seek to achieve.
Some meditations have no specific goal in mind.
Consciousness would not exist if there were no free will. Consciousness is the best definition of 'you', and we use it to weigh up options and select a course of action.
In a deterministic world, everything needs something to "determine" it. If not, the chain of determinations wouldn't exist, making the deterministic world impossible.
It is not true that a deterministic universe requires some kind of infinite regress. This claim is based on human intuitions about the nature of time which aren't supported by current science.
The universe could just have always existed, or could be part of some set of possible universes.

The existence of consciousness does not imply the existence of free will. In a freedom-less world, we can still evaluate options and decide on a course of action, but given the same sensorial parameters, our choice would be the same every time.
To evaluate sensorial parameters, we don’t need consciousness. Therefore consciousness must be more than an evaluation mechanism,  i.e. free will.
Consciousness might be considered as an instinctive analysis mechanism without free will.
"Instinctive analysis" happens usually in the subconscious, there no free will is proposed. Consciousness involves an agent, which must be free for consciousness to have a meaning.
Consciousness doesn't require free will in order for it to have purpose. Consciousness facilitates reflection on experiences.
In a deterministic world, reflection on experience is useles as conscious reflection on experience is not needed to learn.
The immune system has many learning mechanisms without any evidence of consciousness.
Consciousness is to a brain as the thumb is to a hand. It is a product of evolution. It could be argued that our episodic memory is the keystone of consciousness. It does not confirm free will.
Free will exists only as a mental construct.
Even if free will seems to exist, that is not the same as saying that it actually exists. To claim that something actually exists is to make a claim about objective reality.
Free will could be an illusion that only feels real.
Optical illusions are great examples of things that humans consistently experience, but do not accurately reflect reality.

Being as the reality of our existence is merely based on our perception of it, and we don't view ourselves as an illusion even though that may be what we are, if we perceive that free will exists, than to us it exists.

Existing as an illusion, mirage or figment of one's imagination is not the kind of existence in dispute. Subjective experience does not make reality. There are not as many realities as there are brains, there is only one reality in our shared timeline.
If the illusion of free will is good and complicated enough, then there is no need for real free will, because the illusion would function in the same way and produce the same effects.

It is essential for human beings to react to the world, make choices, and have agency. Even if free will is an illusion, it is necessary for human beings because it makes agency, making choices, and interacting with the world possible.
People who believe in their power to choose make changes and improve others' lives, giving meaning to the human life.
Believing or not in the power to choose - or free will - does not imply on adding to others' lives.
There are other equally plausible phenomena from which people could derive value in living (e.g. the quality of experience). Therefore, freewill is not the only possible meaning to live.
Humans' reason to live is to survive long enough to procreate successfully.
Without the fundamental drive to procreate successfully, our species would not have developed and thrived as it has.
This is an unreasonable simplification of natural pressures to procreate. The human organism is more capable and complex than other organisms who merely spawn, procreate, and die.
While procreation was once of paramount importance for our species, due to overpopulation and the current status of resources, it is no longer of primary importance.
It is not necessarily the case that there are any objective reasons to live.

As we can never truly know whether the free will we feel we have is real or illusory, there is no difference to matter. This means that the illusion of free will can be rightly understood as free will itself.
The answer to the question will never present itself in a way that we can perceive within our limited consciousness. We should accept our limits and enjoy the ride.
Statement contradicts itself, starts by saying free will does not exist, ends by saying it does. The illusion of free will is, by definition, not free will.

The appearance of a thing can be the thing itself.
I.e. An image of a mirror is both the appearance of the image in the mirror, and an image in the mirror.
Many people use the concept of Free Will to explain "The Problem of Evil", so at least in that context the truth matters.
An illusion, even if consequential, is not real.
Illusions rarely produce all of the effects that real things would produce.

Instead of associating realness with absolute truth, it is more accurate to associate it with the consequences and effects something produces because empirical studies can only measure and evaluate effects.
The claim is a claim about objective reality, and is thus self defeating.
Free will can only be imagined because empirically testing it would require the ability to go back in time in order to observe past events.
To require that one return to a specifically designated time, and choose the formerly discarded option, as the only acceptable proof is untenable.
If we did not have free will, then we could never really know what free will means as a concept.
By imagination, humans can combine terms and think of new concepts that don't exist.
Even if someone were to return to a previous time and observe people making different choices, that would not imply free will.
Mental constructs are the functional result of existing realities.
"Mental constructs" exist. Therefore, free will exists.
While one can easily achieve a level of incoherency that renders "a mental construct" useless in practice, it is impossible to conceive of a new idea that does not have reference to reality.

It's more valid to consider the self to be made of physical structures, that owns and is responsible for itself, than to consider the will as only valid if it were a magical unobservable force that permeates the physical body and rules of nature.
Free will is not a description of a reality in the physical world. If it were there would be definite physical proof of it.
The same could be said of causality, which is the main principle obstructing the whole idea of free will.
Causality fits with observations. Free will is not compatible with observed causality.

Both causality and free will are mental constructs; two ways of defining the same human experience. In the same way that 'Light' may be observed to be a wave form or a stream of photons but never both at the same time, the two are mutually exclusive.
Moral responsibility cannot exist without free will. Since moral responsibility does exist, free will must also exist.

Judicial systems, all over the world, are a result of acting on the premise that an individual has free will, otherwise there's no reason to put responsability on someone for his actions and absurd to punish someone for something he's not responsible, but mearly an effect of a deterministic chain.
Without any judicial systems, people wouldn't see the consequences of committing a crime, thus crime rate would be much higher. Judicial systems are altering the deterministic chain.

Many judicial systems actively avoid consideration of "punishment" when sentencing, and instead focus on protection of society, behavioural change and rehabilitation, precisely because a perpetrator cannot be held responsible for a deterministic chain of events.
Even if a particular judicial system is built on a premise that an individual has free will, that does not make the premise true.
People are made responsible for their actions through the systems of laws of their country, city, or state.
If fear of legal penalty enforced by law system be used as a moral compass, then there would be no reason to take responsibility for one's actions if chances of getting caught were slim to none.
Moral responsibility refers to the intent of actors rather than their capacity to act freely (Section 3.4.3).
Even if their actions are pre-determined, we cast blame on the reasons one has for acting. The immorality of one's intent does not rely on freedom.
The existence of moral responsibility is itself debatable.
It's desirable but we can't conclude it exists just because we want to. Not in a way that we can bring into existence anything it would require by modus tollens.
If the existence of moral responsibility as a fact of natural law is debatable, perhaps it is a free construct, instigated by none other than human will.
Evidence that the concept of moral responsibility exists does not impact the existence of moral responsibility in the world.
Moral responsibility exists on the basis of cause and effect, which itself is evidence against free will.
Cause and effect do not allow for moral responsibility, since all actions are predetermined and no other action could have been taken.

Moral responsibility has more to do with our innate sense of fairness or balance, than about accountability, or punishment. Therefore, intuitions regarding moral responsibility do not require free will.
Morality is a meme that is evolving based on it's ability to improve our lived experience. This does not require free will.

The concept of moral responsibility varies widely among cultures. In some cultures responsibility extends to a person's community, with no claim to be relying on any individual's agency. Therefore moral responsibility is possible without free will

Morality is the product of social conditioning. It is possible to train a cat to use a human toilet, this does not imply that the cat has free will and decides to use the toilet, it has simply been conditioned to do so.
Conditioning the cat's toilet habits evidently traces back to the imposition of will freely exerted by the human trainer; thus any argument about the cat's freedom is irrelevant.

"Moral Responsibility" will evolve into "Moral Acceptable Behaviour" in order to fulfill what society needs (rules to protect the survival of the tribe). Free will will no longer be needed as a concept, in order to fulfill that need.
Moral responsibility is consequent, not antecedent to free will and its existence is questionable
The presumption of free will is used as a factor in determining the morality of an action, therefore moral responsibility must be consequent to free will.

E.g. If someone commits murder, whether or not they could have chosen otherwise is highly relevant. If they were coerced to pull the trigger then they are held less culpable and the person who forced them to pull the trigger is moreso.
Our best scientific evidence is based on mental constructs, like human experience.
For free will to be a mental construct, implausible things like solipsism - the belief that only the self exists - would have to be true.
Since it is unlikely that solipsism is true, free will is likely not a mental construct.
Solipsism is only supported if everything is mentally constructed. Even if free will is a mental construct, that does not provide strong evidence for solipsism being true.
Lived experience and human observation are highly reconstructive and flawed and therefore cannot falsify determinism.
There is neuroscientific evidence that people often misremember the order of events, which can create the illusion that choice precedes certain actions.
Free will outside of determinism would, by definition, require some determinate factor which would be impossible to observe.
If determinism is unfalsifiable, then it fails as a theory.
This use of human observation to discredit the validity of human observation, is a self defeating line of argumentation.
Thought and consciousness exist in humans and are immaterial; as such, we are not solely subject to physical laws.
Thoughts do not accelerate towards Earth under gravitational attraction until they reach terminal velocity, for example.
While free will might not exist in the sense of laws of physics or deterministic universe, it does exist in the sense of psychology and sociology.
Thoughts and Consciousness can be altered by modifying the consistence of the brain and brain functions. Thus contradicting the second half of the argument that they are not subject to physical laws.
Whether they are physical or not, the process by which thoughts evolve is either deterministic or random.

Free will is defined as the "ability to act at one's own discretion".  The fact that we, as humans, are controlled biologically by our internal parts/processes does not show that we, as humans, are not the one in control, because we are the sum of our parts.

The internal processes which control all of our "parts" (cells, physiological processes, ...) all answer deterministic rules (described through physics, chemistry and biology). Arguing that we are the sum of these parts therefore seems to confirm that the human behavior is deterministic as well, and that there is no such thing as free will.
Activities that involve choices provide evidence for the existence of free will.
The act of debating in itself is a proof of free will's existence.
Debating is no more a support of the concept of "free will," than dancing, eating, and sleeping are. It's just an activity like all of the rest.
These other activities do not necessarily presuppose that there are different options. Debating / thinking only makes sense if we can decide between different options.
A computer program could participate in a debate.
The act of debating is proof of determinism as it shows that belief is not a choice, and when presented with the right evidence or logic, one is forced to understand or believe something.
People consider and weigh the benefits of various courses of action countless times in their lives. They would not do that if there were no choices available to them.
Our ability to stop ourselves mid-action suggests free will.
When people overcome a physical addiction, that is evidence that we are capable of influencing our biochemical function and ultimately structure.

Chess computers come up with different plans after thinking for a longer period of time. If a chess computer would control a robot arm that plays chess it could stop itself mid-action without suggesting free will.A live view of the inner workings of a chess engine changing it's opinion.

Without evidence that a decision to stop was made absent motivations caused by outside forces (though all our motivations result from outside forces) a decision to stop acting is no more evidence for free will than our talking an action is evidence for free will.
The fact that we regret certain decisions, suggests that there was indeed free will.

Regretting decisions can be interpreted as a deterministic system that has acquired more information. After the outcome of an event you have more information, therefore the system might have done a different action
Rather than suggesting there was free will, it merely suggests that we feel as if there is free will. This is entirely consistent with the concept of free will being an illusion.
An algorithm can also be programmed to "consider and weith the benefits of various courses of action" - and it does not have free will.
This confuses the existence of free will with the existence of options. Choosing among options does not imply that one chooses freely.

Decision-making implies choice. If rationality is essentially about making decisions and decisions don't existed strictly speaking without free will, then reason and determinism are incompatible after all.

Any decision-making or choice-making is based on information analysis, which involves conscious thinking. This isn't possible without external sources of influence and stimuli, making it clear, that we are fully bound by these stimuli.
One can make two or more different decisions in response to the same external sources and stimuli, thus it doesn't corroborate determinism.
Any variables are just other sources of influence or stimuli, as totally identical individual conditions are very unlikely.
It doesn't follow that if we rely on sensory input from the external world to make a decision that we are acting in determined response to it.
One may look out the window, see that it is raining, yet still walk out without an umbrella.
This is a false statement. Some decisions are not made by information analysis.
Digital physics  and other information theories argues the opposite.

Decisions are less of choice but more of a reaction. You arrive at a point in time where you must decide, you evaluate the options you perceived, you choose on the basis of experience. But your experience is solid. Unless the past is completely irrelevant, simply that your mother told you to be nice at some point in your life will have an impact on all further choices. Everything in and before your life has had some form of impact on you and has led you to react in such a way that mirrors you.
Unless the decision is exclusively reaction, and absent choice, free will still is present to an extent. "More of x" and "less of y" isn't proof. It's an explication of your impression of decision.
The origin of a person's decision are determined by actions unknown to them. Until we know the true origin, this statement is unfounded
Each choice only has one outcome that becomes reality.
One may still have a will, as in choices they can make autonomously. But their supposed will is not free, since it's bound by only having one outcome.
Even if alternate timelines exist where a different choice is made, in each of those timelines there is only one outcome as well.
Free will refers to the existence of a choice between two potential actions, not for the possibility of choosing two contradictory actions at once and both actions actually being taken.

This argument is for the discussion of free will irrelevant: even if each choice has only one outcome that becomes reality, it could be that we have a free will, because free will postulate that we can choose between choices, and each potential chosen choice can have this own "real" outcome. But what it is at stake is not the question, if the choosen choices have one outcome, but if the actor can really choose between choices.
Choices must have motivations.
One's choices are determined by the incentives that precede them, leaving no room to intervene.
Thought is not free. Thoughts affect actions. Actions cannot therefore cannot be free.
We cannot predict what our next thought will be. Anything that we have complete control over, we can predict. Therefore, we do not have complete control over our thoughts.
There are various religious and spiritual teachings that imply we have free will.
Judeo-Christian scriptures teach that God has given us the freedom to choose our actions.
God wants humans to be morally good, and the only way that we can be morally good is if we have free will.
God's reward to obedient human beings requires obedience to be freely chosen.
God's judgement in many religions requires people to have chosen evil to "deserve" any kind of punishment.
If we did not have free will, we would be amoral.
To argue based on what God wants, we must first prove that a god exists, then prove what that god wants.

Most people don't believe animals have free will yet we often punish or reward animals according to their behaviour (E.g, dogs), so clearly, it is not necessary. Your dog can do something 'bad' even though it doesn't freely choose it in the libertarian sense.

The Book of Mormon teaches: "men are free according to the flesh; and all things are given them which are expedient unto man. And they are free to choose liberty and eternal life, through the great Mediator of all men, or to choose captivity and death, according to the captivity and power of the devil." 2 Nephi 2:27
The Old Testament teaches: "I have set before you life and death, blessing and cursing: therefore choose life, that both thou and thy seed may live." Deuteronomy 30:19
The Old Testament states: "choose you this day whom ye will serve." - Joshua 24:15

The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (The "Mormon" Church) teaches that free will is essentially the God's plan of Happiness for mankind and our freedom to choose is one of mankind's greatest blessings.

The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints also teaches that one of Satan's greatest sins was that he "sought to destroy the agency [i.e. free will] of man, which I, the Lord God, had given him."
Some religious thinkers reject the concept of free will, such as Martin Luther in "On The Bondage of the Will."
The existence of God itself is an intense debate in and of itself, with no consensus on its nature.
The Hindu faith teaches that though we do not choose the circumstances we are now in and the karma that will result from our choices, we are free to choose our actions.
Though Muslims believe in divine destiny, that all that will happen is written on the preserved tablet, Allah's awareness of what will happen does not force mankind's hand. Mankind has free will.
In this example, Allah's awareness of what will happen leaves no agency for mankind. Mankind will do exactly what Allah knows they will do.
The existence of a God or deity precludes our having free will.
Islam undermines belief in the existence of free will.
Islam (like many religions) contains the concept of (qadar), which is incompatible with free will.
The way I read it, qadar is about events as opposed to personal choice of action.
God's omniscience regarding our "choices" may mean that a classical God cannot give us free will.
God's purported omnipotence and omnipresence would necessarily dictate that all choices would proceed according to God's will, not ours.
The concept of a God that is watching and judging would imply that he has given free will
If God is truly omnipotent, then he must have the ability to give us free will. Omnipotence necessitates to have the ability to create logic and make it bend to His will to give us free will.

True "free will" that is unrestrained and undetermined by any other will is only possible for a being that has supreme power (otherwise there would always be a more powerful being whose will could override ours). In order to give us free will, God would have to abdicate his own will to us, therefore giving up his omnipotence.
The impact of God omnipotence and omniscience on human free will depends on the content of his will, not just its existence.
A omniscient God that would "not care" would have a neutral will about mankind, meaning that it would have no impact on the existence of free will.
God could consider "free will" as more important than its domination over the universe, making himself a willing "victim" of the free choices made in the universe.
It is an extraordinary display of submitting to others for an omnipotent god to demonstrate that they have granted other beings free will.
A deity prescribing moral benefits or penalties (e.g. Heaven and Hell) in return for behaviour is incompatible with the concept of free will (p. i).
An Omnisciencent being who can see the future, contradicts freewill as it requires a predetermined future to exist.
A predetermined future doesn't contradict free will

Predetermined meaning also “perceived in advance” in the context of the omniscience of the future, must not be confused with the deterministic view of the world in which things are prepared/set in advance by fate - these are homonyms but not synonymous. The fact that I know something does not mean that I cause it.

This is a valid argument only for non-omnipotent beings. For a being that has supreme power and is said to be the only "uncaused cause", God's supreme knowledge AND power would necessitate that nothing would ever happen without being at least indirectly caused by Him and the way that he set the universe into motion.
The future, even if it was determined in advance can be “due to” the free choices that will be made by the agents involved. The “future” aspect of a cause may not preclude its validity as a cause.

In the case of the traditional conception of God, he is not only omniscient but is also omnipotent and the creator of the universe, therefore God could have created and set the universe into motion in any way he chose in order to achieve whichever predetermined future he desired.

If there is an infinite number of possible outcomes out of a single action, there is not a single predetermined future, but an infinte number of possible futures. Thus, on Omnisciencent being can know (can "will") all of them, without constraining your choice.
There is no reason to assume that a god's ability to predict the future would necessitate a pre-determined future, as omnipotence entails yet unknown (or even impossible) ways of knowing.
The divine laws associated with the God of classical theism restrict free will.
People can kill independent of divine edicts, proving that they have free will even though God may not wish for a particular thing to happen.
If God is not situated in time, but external to it, he can know our future without depriving us from free will.
According to the Christian God, you are free to choose between certain paths. When He says you are predestined he actually tells you that the path you chose will get you to a particular destination.
No such precise description is given in the Bible.
Omniscience about your choices doesn't have bearing on whether you have free will.  (Omniscience about what you will chose does not imply a constraint on your freedom to choose.)
Since deities are considered to have free will, eventually free will exists, even if humans do not have any.
This may be an argument against particular concepts of God or fate rather than an argument against free will.
It is possible to posit a type of non-classical God who willingly blinds himself to our choices such that He provides us freewill.

In Christianity, Jesus plainly said that He did not know when He would return; only the Father knew that date. (Matthew 24:36) Most Christians hold that Jesus as God knew this information, but willingly blinded himself to it while walking the earth as a human.
Although the claim above is accurate, it addresses a specific bit of knowledge. The Bible never implies that God is unaware of our future actions and choices.
The definition of God given for this discussion includes omniscience. For God to know everything, but not know everything at the same time in the same way is incoherent.
Not knowing a fact by becoming "willfully blind" to that fact is not "the same way" as not knowing a fact. Therefore the contradiction is avoided.
The choice of a specific God is arbitrary and their bearing on any argument predicated on sharing beliefs.
Some gods are said to have given free will to some people, but other gods have not purportedly given free will.

Monotheistic theologies tend to explain their philosophical and historical claims, even the actions & existence of God, out of necessity/reasoning and not out of unfalsifiable stories and statements as ancient or modern mythologies would.

Explaining logic through stories is in no way inherently logical or sensible. A story may facilitate understanding, but does not impact the truth or reality of a fact. Buttressing statements with claims from fictional characters does nothing to strengthen a claim.
Belief itself is not really coherent without an assumption of agency with some degree of potential freedom.
This is reverse reasoning. Free will would be an argument for those religions but those religions cannot justify the existence free will.

In a purely scientific, rational discussion surrounding the freedom to make choices, spiritual and religious teachings do not meaningful contribute to our understanding, nor do they present good tools for making such a contribution.
Religious and spiritual teaching may be wrong. It's the same as someone claiming that math and biology teaching says there's no free will.

Religious teachings are generally not exercises in rational critical thinking and often specifically ask those being taught to disregard their critical thinking toolset in favour of unquestioning faith.
Religious and spiritual teachings on free will offer no means to test their veracity or question the source and so should be treated with no more regard than any other anecdote.
Various religions are known to be inconsistent with reality.

Christianity and Judaism include the claim that God created Eve after Adam already existed (and had even named things), which is contradicted by anthropology and evolution that show that genders existed before humans and that humans evolved male and female along side each other from other species.
One from the opposite perspective could claim that various branches of science are known to be inconsistent with reality.

The limits of current science exploring the structural basis for consciousness fall short of explanation of the topic. Thus restricting the conversation to purely scientific description of the topic would leave the discussion incomplete.
Unknowns and incompleteness are not problematic for the scientific process. Despite not fully understanding what the force of gravity is, scientific studies and models remain useful.

In the domain we examine as appropriate to a discussion of free will, both the objective neurological foundations of the phenomena (read biology) and metaphysics are necessary for a robust and informed discussion. We will necessarily have recourse to speaking in terms of the extra-physical when discussing such extra-physical concepts as thought and choice.
By definition, scientific truth cannot be irrefutable, since scientific truth must be refutable to be considered scientific.
In practice, science requires that any proposition be subject to repeatable verification.
This would mean the assumptions of the scientific method are unscientific.
Compatibilism asserts that determinism and free will are compatible.
Hard determinism cannot be true because it entails contradictions and paradoxes.
If human actions are entirely deterministic, then this would suggest that no one is responsible for their actions.
In a deterministic world, criminals could not be punished because they were coerced into acting by various (biological, psychological, societal, etc.) forces.
The claim of coercion because of biological, psychological, social factors, etc. is used to exonerate criminals who are believed to have some sort of mental deficiency.
Criminals could still be punished in such a world, since punishment actually results from a societal rejection of the outcomes of some behaviors rather than as a deterrent for freely made choices.
Punishing criminals could be seen as a means to prevent others from being influenced by the criminal acts of others.
Criminals are punished because actions such as murder go against Natural Law, not just because society does not accept their crimes.
The existence of free will is not dependent on whether it would be harmful to society.

Hard determinism suggests that it would be possible to predict the future, given detailed knowledge of the present. But this in turn suggests that one could know this prediction and yet paradoxically be unable to create a different outcome.
If the world is deterministic, then all of our beliefs regarding the existence or non-existence of free will are predetermined.
Predetermination does not invalidate the proven effectiveness of logic.
The notion of free will is contradictory, which suggests that there must be an alternative to strict determinism and absolute freedom.
The notions of 'freedom' and 'will' are incompatible, making the expression 'free will' an oxymoron.
If given the same input we would choose consistently, which would be a true “will”, we are not really free - just bound by the circumstances of our inputs.
Will can be defined as similar to determination, which is the act of deciding definitely and firmly. If we choose differently for no reason, this cannot be considered "definitive" or "firm".

Free will does not assume that we choose differently "for no reason". It assumes that we choose differently because we will to choose differently. The objection begs the question by assuming that free will is impossible.

To ignore the agency of the chooser (by claiming there is "no other reason" for a different choice) is to evaluate Free Will theory in terms of the deterministic worldview, which is fallacious. Each worldview must be evaluated on its own terms.
According to Mind-Body Dualism, "will" refers to something other than mere neuro-chemical processes. There is a distinction between a person and the body he inhabits.
What makes my choice a free choice is not what I choose, but that I could have chosen differently.
Given the exact same choice under the exact same circumstances you would always make the same choice. The idea that you could change the past is not proof of freewill.

If given the same input we are capable of choosing something other that what we would choose, which would be freedom, we really would not have a will,  Our chooser is more like a Plinko board, a random system.
Will can be defined as the power of control over one's own actions or emotions. If the "control" is actually random, changing for no reason, it cannot be seen as being my own.
If my choices are consistent with my self-defined identity, this does not make my choices random, but simply unique.
A person can be described as a chain of unique decisions nobody else has made. My identity is this chain of unique choices.
The original cause of many decisions for a human being may be one of his own freely willed decision/choice.
The definition of free will should not include being free from our own choices, because that definition would be self-referential. Obviously, we cannot choose anything different from what we choose.
Will, as a choice according to preferences, is not compatible with a non-deterministic freedom, independent of preferences.
'Free will' does not imply that one's choice cannot be influenced by their pre-existing preferences.
Free will implies an ability to deliberate and choose one's actions, taking their preferences and desires into consideration, while not being beholden to them.
The (pre)existing preferences would be set by the individual's interaction with their environment, and therefore choices influenced by existing preferences would still be deterministic.

Choices can be nondeterministic and have external causes at the same time, by being a combination of environmental factors and free will. For instance by freely choosing which existing preferences to use to base your choice on.

"Free will" is an expression taken to mean that one has agency, or the ability to make a choice from various courses of action. The fact that to a given individual the words "free" and "will" have associations that make the literal joining of the two incompatible is not relevant.
Homonyms are not synonyms, similarly expressions can mean something completely different than the words composing them.
If the expression "free will" is a relevant expression of the concept of agency, if "free will" is oxymoric that would demonstrate that the concept of agency is incoherent.

If there is no better way than "free will" to explain what agency means for a given individual with a practical everyday vocabulary, it is most likely irrelevant to a practical everyday life. And since agency is claimed to be an everyday feature, it would be unlikely that it exists.

The paradox observed in the expression "free will" applies to "agency" if agency is a simple "ability". Let's consider a given individual in a given situation of choice. If this ability can only be exercised consistently (consistent choices), then this is indistinguishable from "Determinism". If it leads to inconsistent choices, this is a random system  independent from the individual, and therefore still indistinguishable from "Determinism".
Agency means that the individual is the cause of the action; and that the individual could have caused a different action, had he wished.
Agency is extraordinarily easy to define. It is the ability to do or refrain from doing anything that is possible, given physical laws.

By mentally simulating probable outcomes of actions and selecting an action based on the result: even in a pure, cold, deterministic cost-benefit algorithm we experience a crude deterministic freedom which serves as a baseline.

Minds have/are a constant feedback loop, aware of the state of our capable actions, our environment and ourselves through time. Even were actions ultimately deterministic; as self-reflection and awareness exists, we consider the paths which we are free to take.
Societies, language, relationships and other interactions strongly bias minds toward constant, iterative change in the optimization of choice, increasing the degree of freedom.
Behaviors which reach adoption are aggregates of individual optimization strategy which feedback into society, language, etc.
Even in a deterministic model, societies, language, relationships and other interactions function as testbeds where individuals explore unknown outcomes for useful outcomes.

There are two kinds of freedom to be taken into account: Freedom as the possibility to act on a will, and as the possibility to form a will without outside influence in the first place. One form can exist without the other.

Brains, and neural tissue in general, are self-programming and self-specializing according to stimulus and organization in the body. We each at minimum have "unique will", which may or may not be completed with "freedom" by other claims.
In Non-Linear Dynamical accounts of human development, the brain is a complex self-organizing system which couples with its environment.
"Free will" can be defined using logically coherent language, we just haven't figured out how to do it yet.
If we are the author of our thoughts, this would require us to plan our thoughts, thinking about them before they arise in our mind, which is impossible.
We are the authors of our actions, not our thoughts, it is what we choose to do according to our will in disregard to influence from outside or inside that gives us control over ourselves.
Our thoughts control our actions, otherwise the action is involuntary. If we are not the author of our thoughts, and our thoughts dictate out actions, then we are not the author of our actions.
Improvisation requires no planning, thus if thoughts are improvised they can be owned without being planned.
Improvisation is rapid planning and execution.
There are more things we can do with a free will than just being the author of our thoughts.

As long as the will is self originated, and not the product of outside causes(not to be conflated with influences), then it is not illogical for a thought to not have planning, or even a logical requirment that the will would have prior planning.
Regardless of whether the will is self originated, if it is unplanned, it is involuntary.

Either human behaviors are (with sufficient information) predictable, or they are not. In the first case, one could, in principle, predict what someone will do. In the second case, not even the actor could predict what they would do, and actions would be random. In either case, there is no opportunity for libertarian free will.
Something that is not predictable does not need to be completely random.
Only the notion of "complete free will" is contradictory. The notion of "some level of free will" is still plausible without being contradictory.
A choice on which problem to focus your attention on can be seen as a lower level of free will then the creation of thoughts.
It is decomposing free will that is illogical, as decomposing the motion of an arrow is illogical, as was mentioned by Zenon d'Élée.
The appearance of paradoxes may indicate an attempt to fit truth into an inadequate model.
Compatiblism is widely supported and popular within the academic community.
The popularity of compatiblism does not provide strong evidence for its truth or accuracy.
The consensus among academics lends reasonable credibility to the accuracy of a position relative to, say, the general public.

There is more than one type of compatibilism, including determinism with respect to decision-making, but still with moral responsibility. While compatibilism is broad, in the quoted survey free will is narrow, referring only to libertarian free will.

Libertarian free will and determinism are classically considered as extremes and the absence of precise definitions for these may have pushed moderate/soft libertarians and determinists to answer "lean toward" compatibilism

Classic libertarianism states that "one's actions are not determined by anything prior to a decision, including one's character and values, and one's feelings and desires" - which is obviously an extreme. source
In a multiple choices survey, respondents generally tend to answer with the moderate or neutral proposition.
Philosophers should have strongly affirmed positions since this philosophical question is seen as fundamental to our decision-making processes.
This is not a survey of professional philosophers, thus it is not representative of the broader philosophical community.
Philosophy graduate students and non-tenured philosophy faculty are members of the academic philosophical community, and thus are a representative sample.
Deterministic causes can be controlled and understood by human cognition.
If determinism were true, human cognition would also be pre-determined.
It's possible that some events could be deterministic while some people think what they have free will.
If those people's thoughts don't have an effect on the event, then it's still deterministic, while also including some free will.
Causes could be calculated if we had an infinite precision, but human perception and cognition is finite, so we can't understand deterministic causes
The concept of free will that is used in everyday life (e.g. in systems of justice) does not require a contra-causal mechanism, thus determinism isn't relevant to the question.
The word 'autonomy' fits this definition better than 'free will' as it is free of the metaphysical claims attatched to the concept of 'free will'.
The justice system is based on the contra-casual mechanism, in that people are expected to have the free will to make (and be held accountable for) decisions, yet causality is accepted in most cases.
There can be a consistent will to act in a particular way due to supposed impersonal and indeterminate causes. Free will need not to be without prior cause.
If there is a cause for choosing an action, then it was not the will that chose the action, but rather the cause that sparked the will to choose the action.
Causes are contingent, and therefore not set in stone from the start.

Contingent causes can be impersonal and determinate causes. If human actions and choices are reducible to impersonal, determinate causes, it does not follow that human actions and choices are reducible to necessary causes.
If there are no finite objects that universally and necessarily determine the human will, then all finite objects contingently determine the human will. Freedom is, therefore, possible.

IF the set of starting conditions (BB) obtain, THEN they determine the present set of conditions. Each moment, therefore, obtains contingently (and not of necessity) as determined by the previous moment's conditions.
If the universe is infinite then the number of variables to determine an action is infinite, thus indeterminable. It is therefore both deterministic and free.

If the number of universes increases over time as more decision points appear,  then each universe would be deterministic, but a decision would result in is moving from a parent universe to one of a number of children universes.
Determinism is a requirement for free will.
If effects are not produced by causes, then will can't direct action.
If effects happen without causes, there can be no consistency in motivation, making it random. This can't be called "will".
Hard determinists reject compatibilism for trying to pair determinism with free will, claiming that there is no room for freedom if actions are truly bound by universal laws or forces.

Obviously, the belief that "determinism is true, and determinism is incompatible with free will" is incompatible with free will. This only seems anything like an argument against compatibilism because of a terminological game.
Without causation, "free will" would be nothing but random acts that come from no perspective, have no motivation, serve no intent, and have no continuity.
Determinism is compatible with the illusion of free will, not free will itself.

Compatibilism looks at the consequences traditionally ascribed to free will, such as "personal responsibility", and argues that those consequences are available under determinism. This perspective may be valuable, but does not make the will non-deterministic.
This statement implies that non-determinism is a requirement of free will. Compatibilism argues precisely that this is not the case.
If free will is a contradictory concept, then "free will itself" *is* an illusion.
In this situation, the only thing binding one's actions is one's will.  Therefore the will is truly free, even if the action taken can be determined by an analysis of the will of the actor.

Compatibilists often abridge the concept of free will. For instance, some argue that a person's ultimate choices are pre-determined, but they freely create their own motivations. This does not constitute truly free will.
This is a weak man argument, that selects an easy-to-refute version of compatibilism and refutes it while implying it to be the standard.
